<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's New Housing Price Up Slightly in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada's new housing price index was
up 0.2 percent in March compared with the same period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time since June 1994 that the annual change
has been positive, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
The composite index increased 0.1 percent from February to
March 1997. This is the fifth consecutive month that the index has
registered a gain.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada attributed the improvement in housing markets
in recent months to "higher consumer confidence coupled with
favorable interest rates."
</P>
<P>
"However, the competitive nature of housing markets continued
to moderate prices increases in a number of surveyed cities," the
federal agency noted.
</P>
<P>
Annual housing construction intentions were up 23.2 percent in
the first quarter of 1997 compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
And according to Canada Mortgage and Housing, the annual pace
of housing starts was also up 37.6 percent for the first quarter
compared with the same period a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
