<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Grand Metropolitan to Merge with Guinness Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's two drinks giants Grand
Metropolitan (GrandMet) and Guinness Monday announced a surprise
20 billion pounds (32.5 billion US dollars) merger to create the
world's seventh largest food and drinks company, GMG Brands.
</P>
<P>
The merger will also form the world's leading branded spirits
and wine group with combined spirits sales of over 100 million
cases a year.
</P>
<P>
The companies said that the merger would generate cost savings
of about 175 million pounds (283.5 million US dollars) a year in
the third year of trading.
</P>
<P>
Guinness chairman Tony Greeener said that it was possible there
would be around 2,000 job losses out of a combined global
workforce of 85,000.
</P>
<P>
But they would be distributed around the world and would take
place gradually over three years and a minority would be in the
UK, he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Guinness shareholders will retain their shares
in the renamed company, some 47.3 percent of GMG Brands, while
GrandMet shareholders will get one new GMG share for each GrandMet
share they hold, around 52.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shareholders stand to gain from share buy-backs worth 2.4
billion pounds (3.9 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The two companies do not expect the deal, which needs approval
from regulatory authorities as well as shareholders, to be opposed
by any official.
</P>
<P>
Joint chairman George Bull said that the product were
complementary, and the group would still have less than 10 percent
of the world's accessible spirits market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
