<HEADLINE> Dutch Minister Calls for EU Crime Prevention Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union should set up a
network in which member states can learn from each other's
experience in crime provention policies, Dutch Justice Minister
Winnie Sorgdrager said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sorgdrager told an EU seminar, held in the Dutch seaside town
of Noordwijk, "If we European wish to prevent an explosive growth
in our prison systems...we need effective policies to prevent
rather than just combat crime."
</P>
<P>
She argued that crime prevention should tackle offences outside
"traditional" areas such as burglary or street crime, and look into
prevention environmental crimes and corruption.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said the effectiveness of crime prevention had been
proven in the Netherlands with crime figures having been stabilized
over the past ten years and a reduction in crime since 1996.
</P>
<P>
A police agency called Europol coordinates the exchange of
information between the 15-nation bloc's national police forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
