<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Health Assembly Pays Special Attention to POPs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The 50th World Health Assembly today
adopted a resolution on the promotion of chemical safety, with
special attention to persistent organic pollutants (POPs).
</P>
<P>
12 POPs including polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), dioxins,
furans, aldrin, dieldrin, DDT, endrin, chlordane,
hexachlorobenzene (HCB), mirex, toxaphene and heptachlor have been
assessed by the International Program on Chemical Safety (IPCS),
which concluded that there was sufficient evidence to demonstrate
the need for international action on these substances.
</P>
<P>
"None of the organochlorine pesticides contained in the list of
12 POPs is currently recommended for use in agriculture, even
though their use in this context is still sometimes reported,"
IPCS Director Dr Michel Mercier said. "The POPs enter the food
chain as a result of contamination of water, air or soil. Some
populations that eat large amounts of fish or wild animals rich in
fats may thereby be exposed to higher POP levels than the average
population."
</P>
<P>
According to a press release by the World Health Organization
(WHO), of the 12 POPs under consideration, DDT is the only
insecticide still in use for public health purposes, in particular
for malaria and leishmaniasis control, but it continues to be
misused in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
On adopting the resolution, the World Health Assembly called on
members "to take steps to reduce reliance on insecticides for
control of vector-borne diseases through promotion of integrated
pest-management approaches in accordance with WHO guidelines, and
through support for the development and adaptation of viable
alternative methods of disease vector control". It also called on
them "to ensure that the use of DDT, for public health purposes,
is limited to government-authorized programs that take an
integrated approach and that strong steps are taken to ensure that
there is no diversion of DDT to entities in the private sector".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
