<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.African Deputy President on Mobutu-Kabila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The proposed second round
talks between Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko and rebel leader
Laurent Kabila is the last chance for a negotiated peace
settlement for the Zairean crisis, South African Deputy President
Thabo Mbeki said today.
</P>
<P>
If agreement is not reached between the rival parties, "then
in reality it opens the way to a military solution being the only
option," Mbeki told journalists in Cape Town, the legislative
capital of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks are reportedly due to be held on Wednesday
aboard South African naval vessel the Outeniqua in the Congolese
port Pointe Noire.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the meeting is the last chance to resolve the
conflict peacefully, Mbeki said, "I think as things stand we are
in that kind of danger that the meeting on wednesday may very
well be the last chance to find a negotiated solution to this
crisis."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who has headed international mediation efforts in the
Zairean conflict, said he would make last-ditch effort to secure
agreement on the principle issues that needed to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
The principle points related to the timetable in which Mobutu
should hand over power to a transitional authority and the
composition of the transitional body.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu's role during the period of transition and how early he
will retire from power also need to be agreed, Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
Both the South African mediators and United Nations special
envoy to Zaire Mahomed Sahnoun were consulting both sides to "try
and move towards a position where these principle issues can be
resolved on Wednesday".
</P>
<P>
" We are hopeful that it will be possible to reach this
agreement... If this agreement is not reached it opens the way to
a military solution being the only option," Mbeki warned.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu and Kabila held their first face-to-face talks aboard
the South African naval vessel on May 4, with the two sides
agreeing to hold second round talks within eight to 10 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
