<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 4,000 in Iran's Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from a killer quake
in east Iran rose to 4,000 today while the number of injuries
exceeds 6,000, the state-run television said here today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 195 aftershocks have jolted Gaen and
Birjand regions which were rocked by a powerful 7.1-degree
earthquake at Saturday noon.
</P>
<P>
The Geophysics Institute of Tehran University said that the
magnitudes of the aftershocks ranged from 3 to 5.5 degree on the
Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani today visited the
quake-stricken area of Hadji-Abad, about 800 kilometers east of
Tehran. He said that "it is very bitter for me to see such
heartrending scenes here."
</P>
<P>
"Such a calamity has befallen us due to the negligence of the
former monarchial regime toward rural areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that tens of thousands of residential
units resistant to quake should have been built in the
quake-prone areas under the former regime. Now, it would take
years to construct such buildings, he added.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani promised that the government would help those who
have suffered losses in the quake by giving them long-term
interest free loans and grants.
</P>
<P>
He said reconstruction activity would start in the area in
coordination with the Interior Ministry and Ministry of Energy
within the next month.
</P>
<P>
He appreciated the rescue operations and relief activities of
Iranian Red Crescent Society and the Ministry of Health in
setting up makeshift clinics and temporary accommodation for
people.
</P>
<P>
Hamid Mohallati, head of the Emergency Headquarters of the
Red Crescent Society, said that 4,000 tents have been erected at
the quake-hit villages and 3,200 other tents forwarded to the
stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
He said rescue operation is underway in 180 villages by 100
teams consisting of 700 relief workers.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 relief workers have been carrying out rescue
operations along with four C-130 aircraft and six helicopters.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the victims are in urgent need of such
relief goods as tents, blanket, medicine, ambulance, blood,
clothing and foodstuff.
</P>
<P>
It is the strongest earthquake occurred in Iran in the past
eight years. A 7.3-degree quake claimed 40,000 lives in northern
Iran on June 21, 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
