<HEADLINE> Britain Orders Urgent Action over Gulf War Syndrome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new Labor government has
promised urgent action to investigate into the causes and effects
of the so-called Gulf War syndrome.
</P>
<P>
The investigation will examine the possible side-effects of the
drugs taken by British soldiers who fought in the Gulf War in 1991
as protection against chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
In his first policy statement, Britain's new Armed Forces
Minister John Reid today promised to give "urgent attention" to
the complaints of the hundreds of veterans demanding action from
the Government."
</P>
<P>
"We have an obligation to investigate sympathetically and
thoroughly any illness suffered by those who have served their
country and to provide all the resources necessary to treat them,"
Reid said.
</P>
<P>
Under the government plan, significant new resources will be
pumped into extra research and the medical assessment program to
cut the backlog of veterans waiting to be seen by doctors.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that many of the 1,100 veterans suffering from
illnesses have claimed they were ordered to have the vaccines and
tablets without any warning about possible side-effects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
