<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Borrows to Finance Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe government today
admitted it would have no choice but to borrow money to finance
the budget deficit which economists said could again result in
the rise of interest and inflation rates.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa told a budget seminar in the
capital Harare that recourse to borrowing was the only choice as
the International Monetary Fund had withheld crucial aid
following its disagreement with the government's inability to
curb spending and cut fiscal deficit.
</P>
<P>
Western donor countries asked the Zimbabwean government to
reduce the deficit to sustainable levels of at least five percent
of gross domestic product (GDP), a demand Harare refused to
accept.
</P>
<P>
The minister said despite a six percent rise in revenue
generated in the nine months to March 1997 -- which went up to
1.62 billion U.S. Dollars against a budget estimate of 1.52
billion U.S. Dollars, the budget deficit will soar to 11.4
percent of GDP against the target of 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
This was mainly due to unbudgeted civil service wage
increments and bonuses awarded late last year which would require
an additional 364 million U.S. Dollars, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
