<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-12 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Suspension of Turkish Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today expressed welcome to
the Turkish move to suspend its military aircraft overflying the
island country.
</P>
<P>
Manolis Christofides, government spokesman of Cyprus, told
reporters at his daily press briefing that the Cypriot government
welcomed the fact that Turkish military aircraft have not
violated Cyprus' air space in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's move followed a Cypriot government unilateral
decision, announced last month, not to invite Greek military
aircraft to overfly Cyprus during the recent military maneuvers
for the sake of the on-going U.N.-led proximity talks between
the Greek and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot decision was welcomed by many foreign
governments, including Britain, the United States, China as well
as the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has also welcomed the information from Ankara that
Turkey has no plans to overfly Cyprus as long as Greek aircraft
do not overfly the island.
</P>
<P>
"If the Turkish government decides to follow the same tactic
as well, in a bid to display and create an atmosphere of
good-will, this is a matter that concerns that government," the
spokesman said, adding "we welcome this development."
</P>
<P>
He noted that "the Cyprus government considered it right to
establish this kind of climate during the talks and to make this
good-will gesture."
</P>
<P>
This is "a specific halt for a specific period," he said,
adding that "we are not talking about a halt of overflights in
general or a permanent halt."
</P>
<P>
Christofides said it was up to the government to decide
whether to extend this period.
</P>
<P>
Observers here consider these as good-will gestures from the
Greek and Turkish sides amid the recent improvement of the
relations between the two members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have been at odds over this east
Mediterranean strategic island, which has been divided since
Turkish invasion in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, together with Britain, were guarantors of
Cyprus' independence under the 1960 Treaty on the establishment
of the Republic of Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
