<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: India, Pakistan Head for Rapprochement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KURUMBA, the Maldives, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The prime ministers
of India and Pakistan held a face-to-face meeting here today amid
increasing signs of a thaw in the relations between the two arch
rivals in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral
and his Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz Sharif, agreed to establish a
hotline between themselves and set up working groups on various
subjects.
</P>
<P>
They decided to continue the bilateral talks between their two
countries at the foreign secretary-level in Islamabad either by
the end of this month or in the middle of June.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to release all the civilian prisoners detained
in each other's country and relax the restrictions on travel
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The prime ministers' talks covered the whole range of issues
between Pakistan and India, including the Kashmir issue, Pakistani
Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides said the talks were held in a "very constructive and
friendly atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
"The talks are very useful and constructive," Prime Minister
Sharif told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We are personal friends. I like this man very much," said a
smiling Sharif, patting the shoulder of Gujral in front of the
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held after the opening of the Ninth SAARC (South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation) Summit in the Maldive
capital Male, was the first between the prime ministers of the two
countries since April 1993, when Sharif and the then Indian Prime
Minister Narasimha Rao met, also on the sidelines of a SAARC
summit, in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan have fought three wars since independence in
1947 and two of them were triggered by the Kashmir dispute, the
main obstacle to ending the long-time hostility between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting followed two rounds of high-level talks between
the two South Asian neighbors, both of them SAARC members.
</P>
<P>
Their foreign secretaries held the first round of bilateral
talks in New Delhi, capital of India, in late March after a gap of
three years. The last round of talks bogged down in January 1994
due to their differences over the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Before being named prime minister, Gujral, who was then foreign
minister in Deve Gowda's government, held talks with his Pakistani
counterpart, Gohar Ayub Khan, in New Delhi on April 9.
</P>
<P>
"It's positive that they are meeting. They know each other,"
Ayub Khan said on Sunday. But he cautioned that "there is no quick
fix" as Kashmir remains the core issue between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
As a goodwill gesture, the two prime ministers have been
exchanging letters and had a five-minute telephone conversation
recently.
</P>
<P>
Sharif sent a congratulatory message to Gujral last month after
the latter won a vote of confidence in the parliament and said the
selection of Gujral as India's prime minister had boosted hopes
for peace between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Responding to his message, Gujral said he was confident the two
neighbors could reach agreement in many areas during bilateral
talks despite differences on some issues.
</P>
<P>
"With each of us showing a constructive and forward-looking
approach we are confident that our exchanges will be useful and
lead to mutually beneficial results," Gujral said. "I am
determined not to spare any effort in this endeavor."
</P>
<P>
Sharif said he "shared the commitment of his Indian
counterpart, Inder Kumar Gujral, to improving relations between
the two countries."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
