<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Hopes for Settlement With Tribal Insurgents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The peace talks between the
Bangladeshi government and tribal insurgents from the southern
Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) proceeded satisfactorily on the
second day today.
</P>
<P>
Both sides were expecting to reach a settlement on the CHT
issue soon, President of the National Committee on CHT and Chief
Whip Abul Hasanat Abdulla told reporters here tonight.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to give any details of the ongoing peace
talks, the fourth of such meeting since the present government
took power last June.
</P>
<P>
Shantu Larma, head of the Parbatya Chattagram Jana Sahhati
Samiti, the political wing of the armed tribal rebels, was also
present during the short briefing by the chief whip.
</P>
<P>
The talks have entered a crucial phase in the wake of the last
two rounds in the capital Dhaka, at which the negotiators failed
to agree on some vital issues like the expulsion of settlers,
withdrawal of the military from the CHT and land rights for the
tribal people, meeting sources said.
</P>
<P>
The independence-seeking tribal insurgents have been waging a
bloody bush war since the 1970s in the 14,200-square-kilometer
region rich in hydrocarbon deposits and teak and thousands of
people have been killed.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will continue their talks tomorrow morning, the
sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
