<HEADLINE> UK Food Exports Grow 1 pct in 1996 despite Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's exports of food and drink
totaled 10.1 billion pounds (16.4 billion US dollars) in 1996,
one percent up on the previous year, despite the European Union's
worldwide ban on British beef since March 1996.
</P>
<P>
Figures released monday by Food from Britain, the export
marketing consultancy, showed that increases in sales of other
products more than offset the loss of an estimated 453 million
pounds (733.9 million US dollars) of beef sales.
</P>
<P>
Exports of breakfast cereals rose 31 percent to 253 million
pounds (409.9 million US dollars) last year, and 61 percent by
volume. Total cereal sales increased 20 percent to 1.6 billion
pounds (2.6 billion US dollars), making it the second largest
sector after drinks.
</P>
<P>
Of the 10.1 billion pounds of total export value, drinks
accounted for 3.17 billion pounds (5.1 billion US dollars), within
which, beer sales rose 38 percent to 242 million pounds (392
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
France remained Britain's largest export market, buying 1.6
billion pounds (2.6 billion US dollars) UK food and drink.
Excluding meet, sales to France grew 15 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Germany rose 11 percent to 748 million pounds (1.2
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
It was reported that aside from last year, Britain's food and
drink exports have been growing at an annual rate of 8-9 percent,
and the country is now the world's sixth largest food and drink
exporter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
