<HEADLINE> Envoy: Canada Wishes to Contribute Toward Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada is willing to contribute
all it can toward a solution to the protracted Cyprus problem, a
Canadian envoy said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after an hour-long meeting with Cypriot
Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides, Michael Bell, Canadian
Foreign Minister's special representative on Cyprus, said he is
"cautiously encouraged" that a solution to the Cyprus problem can
be found.
</P>
<P>
Bell, who arrived here today on a fact-finding mission, was
appointed by Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy as a special
representative on Cyprus last month.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United Nations initiative on Cyprus is
the most important one and that Canada continues to back it
fully.
</P>
<P>
Bell said he will talk with U.N. Under-Secretary for
Political Affairs, Sir Kieran Prendergast, after the latter's
visit to Cyprus, which starts on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said Canada, as part of heightened international interest
shown over Cyprus in recent months, "wishes to see the Cyprus
problem resolved."
</P>
<P>
The Canadian envoy added it is too early to determine how much
his country can do to help solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
According to the Canadian envoy, he will be visiting
Athens, Ankara, Brussels, London, Bonn and The Hague after his
four-day visit to the island.
</P>
<P>
Bell's visit is part of intensified international peace
efforts aimed at seeking an early solution to the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
