<HEADLINE> Cyprus Considers Current Peace Effort Most </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Finding a solution to the
protracted Cyprus problem is a top priority for the Cypriot
government, a government spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides said all Cypriot political leaders have
agreed that it would be "extremely difficult" to turn down an
invitation by the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan for direct
negotiations to solve the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
"We would pay a hefty price if we reject the invitation by the
U.N. Chief," the Spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
It would be "frivolous" to say that differences between the
Greek and Turkish communities in the country cannot be overcome,
Christofides stressed, adding that the Greek Cypriot side will
continue with the U.N.-led proximity talks, aiming at achieving
progress.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that none of the party leaders advising the
president on the Cyprus issue has rejected participation in the
proximity talks or in direct negotiations, if Annan extends an
invitation to President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
"The overall assessment among party leaders is that it may
be the most important recent U.N. initiative for a solution to
the Cyprus question," Christofides said, adding that every stage
of negotiations must be well prepared.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made the statements two days before
U.N. Under-Secretary for Political Affairs Sir Kieran Prendergast
arrives in Cyprus for talks with Clerides and Denktash on Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
Kieran is expected to prepare a report to the U.N. Chief
after his return to New York, later this month, from his
tour in the region, which will take him to Nicosia, Ankara
and Athens.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave
Feissel, Annan will make a decision to call direct talks between
the Greek and Turkish communities in Cyprus soon after Kieran's
visit to the region.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when
the island was divided after the Turkish troops took control
of its northern third in the wake of an Athens-backed coup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
