<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Forestry Conference Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The 15th Commonwealth Forestry
Conference opened today in Zimbabwe's northern resort town of
Victoria Falls.
</P>
<P>
The six-day conference, with its theme "forestry in a changing
political environment: challenges of the 21st century", will
discuss three sub-topics -- the interface between communities,
the state and the private sector, and the technological means of
ensuring sustainability for forestry.
</P>
<P>
Opening the conference, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
said the demand for agricultural land, fuel wood, timber and
other non-timber products were resulting in the annual depletion
of 11 million hectares of tropical forests and woodlands in the
developing world.
</P>
<P>
"While population increase in developed countries has been
matched with economic growth, in developing countries it has been
matched with declining economic growth and worsening
environmental degradation," Mugabe told over 360 delegates from
37 Commonwealth countries.
</P>
<P>
"Consequently, deforestation has several negative environmental
impacts such as soil erosion, global warming, desertification and the
loss of biodiversity," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean president noted there is a need to put monetary
value to the destruction of forests, particularly in rural areas,
to make people appreciate the value of forests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
