<HEADLINE> Kuwait Confronts Iraq at APU Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- While Arab parliamentarians discussed
the issue of Arab solidarity here today, Kuwait and Iraq argued
over steps towards Arab reconciliation and Kuwaiti prisoners of
war (POWs).
</P>
<P>
At a political committee meeting of the Arab Parliamentary
Union today, Chairman of the Iraqi National Council Foreign
Relations Committee Saad Kassem Hamdawi called for the lifting of
the six-year-old U.N. economic embargo on his country.
</P>
<P>
"The sanctions have to be lifted so that Iraq may be able to
reassume its regional role and serve Arab interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Arab nation has long voiced support for Iraq's demand to
lift the embargo imposed for its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, but
little has been delivered yet on the ground.
</P>
<P>
But Kuwaiti representative Mubarak al Khertig urged for the
eradication of the causes of the collapse of Arab solidarity,
notably the 1990 Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"Reconciliation is to be preceded by openness and frank
discussions over who caused this collapse of Arab solidarity,"
said the Kuwaiti representative.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti POWs remain in Iraq and the Kuwaiti people can never
forget the pain the Iraqi invasion has left behind, he added.
</P>
<P>
There are 604 Kuwaiti and third country prisoners in Iraq,
according to files prepared by Kuwait. But Iraq denied it had
detained so many Kuwaiti prisoners in its jails.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi representative proposed, in response to the issue of
Kuwaiti POWs, that the APU General Secretariat and representatives
from the Kuwaiti parliament form an investigation panel to look
into this matter.
</P>
<P>
Several other Arab representatives, including the Egyptian
delegation, intervened to calm the situation.
</P>
<P>
The APU session, originally devoted to enhancing Arab
solidarity which were disrupted during the 1990 Gulf War, thus
turned into a war of words between the two bitter foes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Endorses Spanish, Portuguese Convergence Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- European Union finance ministers
meeting in Brussels on Monday endorsed new economic convergence
plans by Spain and Portugal, two southern European states
struggling to meet the Maastricht treaty's criteria for adopting
the EU's single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
The convergence programs, which were deemed "well balanced
and realistic" by the finance ministers at the meeting, was aimed
to clear the way for the two countries' participation in the first
wave of countries joining EU's Economic and Monetary Union(EMU).
</P>
<P>
The plans anticipate annual GDP(Gross Domestic Product) growth
above three percent between 1998 and the year 2000, allowing for a
progressive reduction in the two countries' budget deficits to 2.5
percent in 1998 and two percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
For the year 2000, the Spanish convergence program
anticipates a deficit equivalent to 1.6 percent of GDP, while the
Portuguese deficit is put as low as 1.5 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Government wishing to qualify for the euro must bring their
1997 budget deficits down to three percent of GDP. They must also
demonstrate that outstanding public debt is approaching 60 of GDP
at a satisfactory pace.
</P>
<P>
In a review of the fiscal situation across the 15-nation bloc,
the ministers have also given Finland and the Netherlands high
marks for their budget-slashing efforts.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have been taken off the list of governments with
so-called excessive deficits, joining Luxembourg, Ireland and
Denmark, the only countries currently in line with the Maastricht
Treaty's requirements for deficits and debt.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers also got an update on proposals of the
European Commission, the EU's executive body, to harmonize EU
energy taxes with a view to extending taxation to all energy
products by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Monday's meeting has also provided the first opportunity for
British finance minister Gordon Brown to meet his EU counterparts
and make clear the new Labour government's position on a wide
range of issues.
</P>
<P>
Meeting EU monetary affairs commissioner Yves Thibault de
Silguy ahead of the ministerial gathering, Mr Brown said that he
would work constructively on EU's planned single currency.
</P>
<P>
In the margin of the minister's meeting, Mr Brown also met with
EU single market commissioner Mario Monti, informing the later his
government's intention to reduce VAT on domestic fuel and power
from eight percent to five percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
