<HEADLINE> ANC Apologizes for Violence in Fighting Apartheid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The ruling African National
Congress has apologized for civilian deaths caused during its
fight against the apartheid regime.
</P>
<P>
The regret is contained in a document submitted by the party
to the government-appointed Truth and Reconciliation Commission,
which is probing apartheid-era crimes, Southern African
Broadcasting Association (SABA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The civilians were killed during bomb attacks on targets such
as mines, office buildings and railway stations in what it said
"a just war against then white minority rule."
</P>
<P>
The document also confessed certain assassinations when the
movement killed its own members or police officers who gave
evidences in trials against ANC members.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki today began to make
an official two-day presentation as part of the second round of
political party submissions to the commission.
</P>
<P>
The National Party, which headed South Africa's last
white-minority government, will get its chance to state its
presentation on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
TRC, headed by retired Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu,
accepted the last applications for amnesty on Saturday midnight
when nearly 8,000 people made their submissions.
</P>
<P>
South Africans making a full confession as their wrongdoings
will be granted legal indemnity from prosecution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
