<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-12 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Releases 5 Iraqi Infiltrators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait released five Iraqi
infiltrators today, Kuwaiti Interior Ministry Public Relations
director Colonel Bader Saleh said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement made public through official Kuwait News Agency
(KUNA) said that "the five infiltrators were arrested by a
coast guard patrol inside Kuwait's territorial waters."
</P>
<P>
It said "they have been sent to the competent authorities
for interrogation and then they were released with the
knowledge of the International Committee of the Red Cross."
</P>
<P>
But it did not give details as to when the Iraqis were
arrested. KUNA said that violators were arrested on February 23
when they attempted to enter the country by sea.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has beefed up security at its borders with Iraq by
installing barbed wire fences connected directly to a computer
network linking its 20 border posts with a central operations
room at the border security headquarters to block infiltrators
from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The fence is 220 kilometers long and runs from the
northern Iraqi border town of Umm Qasr to Salmi in the
south where the borders of Iraq, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia
meet.
</P>
<P>
The strengthened Kuwaiti coast guard has also been perfectly
carrying out its mission in blocking infiltrators and
safeguarding Kuwaiti security, Saleh said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
