<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Agencies, IFRC Provides Emergency Aid to Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program has pledged 200,000 U.S. dollars while the
International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies
(IFRC) has launched a preliminary appeal for 12 million dollars to
assist 60,000 people in Iran following the recent earthquake, a UN
spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Juan Carlos, associate spokesman for UN Secretary General, said
at a news briefing that the United Nations Children's Fund has
pledged 100,000 dollars for water/sanitation and basic health
purposes in the quake affected areas in eastern Iran.
</P>
<P>
UN Department of Humanitarian Affairs has released an emergency
cash grant of 50,000 dollars to cover immediate relief needs, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The worst earthquake to hit Iran since 1990 struck Khorasan
province on Saturday. The earthquake, measuring 7.1 on the Richter
scale, has brought some 2,400 deaths and devastation to the
villages surrounding two major population centers Birjand and
Qaen.
</P>
<P>
With freezing temperatures, whole villages wiped out and the
surviving population fearful of returning to their homes, the
provision of emergency shelter will be the top priority once the
search rescue is completed in over the next 24-36 hours, according
to IFRC.
</P>
<P>
The 60,000 frightened victims will also require food, blankets,
hygiene items and other other relief supplies at least until end
of August, IFRC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
