<HEADLINE> Greek Official on Name of FYROM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The time was "ripe" for Athens and
Skopje to address the name of the Former Yugoslav Republic of
Macedonia (FYROM), Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today, Reppas said that some agreement
might be reached in the U.N.-sponsored talks in New york.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that "any delaying tactics only harm the
other side."
</P>
<P>
He said that Greece was examining "everything" within the
framework of negotiation under the U.N. auspices on the name of
the FYROM, including the possibility of a composite name.
</P>
<P>
By composite name, Reppas was referring to the possibility of a
name containing the word 'Macedonia' or some derivative.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reaffirmed that there was on way that a state
could exist in the region with just the name of "Macedonia".
</P>
<P>
Relations between Greece and FYROM have been strained since the
latter declared its independence in 1991, with Athens objecting to
its neighbor's use of the term of "Macedonia" in any form, saying
that this implied claims to the northern Greek province of the
same name.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the two countries are meeting in New York in order
to solve the name issue, and negotiations are reportedly in
progress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberian Parties Suggest Postponement of Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Eleven of Liberia's 16 political
parties have called for the postponement of the general elections
set for coming May 30 under the revised Abuja Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today from Liberia's capital Monrovia
said the parities issued a statement saying the postponement will
provide an opportunity to address certain issues critical to the
success of the elections.
</P>
<P>
The issues include insecurity, harassment, intimidation and
misinformation, which are prevailing mostly in the rural areas,
and the inability of west Africa's peacekeeping force to deploy
troops to some parts of the country, which raises questions about
security in such areas.
</P>
<P>
The statement also expressed concern about the presence of
"huge cashes of arms and ammunition still hidden that are
periodically being discovered."
</P>
<P>
The parties argued that the postponement will provide more
time for the return of about one million Liberians who fled the
country during seven years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
They also noted the absence of rules and guidelines for the
political parties and the public, the need for voter education
and the alleged domination of the government by factional
appointees.
</P>
<P>
"This condition works negatively against parties with no
representatives in the government, especially when some of the
former factional leaders are contestants in the elections," said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
For example, the media are dominated by former factional
leaders who are "illegally using the country's resources to
advance their personal well-being and electoral prospects," they
said.
</P>
<P>
The parties, therefore, advocated fixing a new date, not
before October 13, for the elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi said the May 30
date is "feasible", based on the assurances by the peacekeeping
force about the security situation in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi has been engaged in consulations within the 16 member
countries of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), which is behind the peacekeeping force in Liberia known
as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has been playing a major role in the peacekeeping
mission in Liberia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
