<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni Prime Minister Abdul Aziz
Abdul Ghani today tendered the resignation of his cabinet to
President Ali Abdullah Saleh in the wake of the parliamentary
elections on April 27.
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni cabinet, in its resignation letter, warmly
congratulated President Saleh on the outcome of the recent
elections, in which the Yemeni ruling General People's Congress
party won a clear majority, according to the Yemen News Agency.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Yemeni people have expressed their adherence
to the republican regime, the objectives of the Yemeni
revolution, the unity of the nation, and the maintenance of
democracy on the basis of popular sovereignty and plurality of
political parties.
</P>
<P>
The resignation letter said that the government, which was
formed on October 6, 1994, had sincerely implemented the
economic, financial and administrative reform program.
</P>
<P>
It said that the elections reflected a new victory for the
Yemeni people and constituted a step forward along the path of
national reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
The letter pointed out that these elections would enhance the
democratic march toward completing the structure of a modern
Yemen state capable of embarking on the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
President Saleh accepted the resignation of the cabinet,
thanking all its members for the efforts they made during their
tenure of office.
</P>
<P>
He hailed the achievements made by the outgoing government,
particularly in dealing with the consequences of the 1994 civil
war and in implementing the economic, financial and
administrative reform program. 
