<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Define Arab Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Leading Arab lawmakers today shared
views on enhancing Arab solidarity through establishing a common
Arab market at the ongoing sessions of the Arab Parliamentary
Union (APU) Council.
</P>
<P>
The committee discussed eight working papers presented by
Egypt, Tunisia, Morocco, Iraq, Sudan, Palestine and Lebanon in
addition to the Arab Economic Unity Council.
</P>
<P>
The working papers agreed on four key targets for the common
market, namely free personal and capital flow, freedom of
residence, work and economic activity, freedom of commodity
exchange and of transit trade.
</P>
<P>
A number of delegations talk the Arab market in the context of
the Arab solidarity, which has been much eroded since the 1990
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
To stand up to the mounting challenges for the developing
countries, the Egyptian delegation said, requires a more solid and
stronger Arab solidarity and the establishment of an Arab common
market and a pan-Arab Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Warning that the Arab world is facing a ferocious Israeli
assault, Lebanese lawmakers said the establishment of an Arab
common market provides a basic means of Arab solidarity and a
challenge to the Mideast market they seek.
</P>
<P>
This opinion was echoed by Jordan, which stressed that
solidarity should begin with economic solidarity and a common Arab
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
