<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Sees No New Risk of Russian Missile Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- A senior Pentagon official said
here today that he saw no new risk of accidental or unauthorized
launch of Russian nuclear missiles against the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on condition of anonymity, the official
said that there is no reason "to believe that there is a
heightened risk of unauthorized or accidental launch of Russian
nuclear missiles."
</P>
<P>
The official made the remarks in response to a report on Monday
in advance of Tuesday's start of two days of Washington talks
between Russian Defense Minister Igor Rodionov and top U.S.
officials on bilateral military ties and security in Europe and
the western Pacific.
</P>
<P>
"I can tell you that I have seen nothing that indicates that
any sort of an incident occurred," the official said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, The Washington Times said that a classified CIA
report indicated recent malfunctions of equipment controlling
Moscow's vast nuclear arsenal had spontaneously switched missiles
to "combat mode" on several occasions, increasing the risk of
unauthorized launch.
</P>
<P>
Rodionov will hold separate talks on Tuesday with Defense
Secretary William Cohen and White House National Security Adviser
Samuel (Sandy) Berger, and meets on Wednesday with Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright before departing for Hawaii and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The talks will focus on increased U.S.-Russian military
cooperation, but also include NATO enlargement, European security
and the situation in the Pacific rim, the Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
The trip will be Rodionov's first to the U.S. as defense minister
and he would meet Cohen for the first time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
