<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Presidential Spokeswoman on Chirac's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The spokeswoman said that during his visit in China, President
Chirac will sign with President Jiang Zemin a political
declaration to push forward the dialogue in all fields between
France and China, and to give a political significance to such
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
This will help the two countries better coordinate their
positions on major international issues, and help them carry out
discussion in the fields of environment protection, public health
and other social issues, she said.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said that France supports China's reform and
opening policy as well as the legal construction of the country,
and reaffirmed that France adopts a policy of dialogue rather than
confrontation over the issue of human rights toward China.
</P>
<P>
On economic cooperation between the two countries, Colonna said
that although bilateral trade has grown over the past several
years, French enterprises now only have taken up 1.7 percent of
the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
She said that France wishes to establish a privileged
partnership with China in economic field, especially in the fields
of airspace industry, nuclear energy, hydro-electricity,
insurances, financial services, and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
She said that 300 French enterprises, including many small and
medium-sized businesses, will display their products at the
Exhibition of French Technology in Shanghai to be inaugurated by
President Chirac on May 17.
</P>
<P>
On cultural cooperations, she said that France will reinforce
bilateral cultural ties through the visit by the president,
especially in the fields of language training and study,
administration and jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette, the Minister of
Equipment, Housing and Transport Bernard Pons, the Minister of
Industry Franck Borotra, the Delegate Minister of Finance and
Exterior Trade Yves Galland and the Delegate Minister of Post,
Telecommunications and Space Francois Fillon, as well as the
leaders of 50 major French enterprises will accompany the
president to visit China. 
</P>
