<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Arab economy and finance ministers have discussed
the economic performance in their countries at a two-day annual
meeting here.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting ending Sunday, the ministers of the 22-member
Arab League (AL) also reviewed reports by the league's five main
financial institutions on their 1996 operations.
</P>
<P>
The five organizations are the Abu Dhabi-based Arab Monetary
Fund, the Arab Fund for Economic and Social Development and the
Inter-Arab Investment Guarantee Corp, which are based in Kuwait,
the Arab Bank for Economic and Social Development in Africa and
the Arab Organization for Agricultural Investment and
Development, which are based in Khartoum, the Sudanese capital.
</P>
<P>
The annual meeting has also attracted Arab central bank
governors and other economic and financial officials, who have
presented reports on the performance of regional economies and
investment activities.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The Iranian government warned here today that it
will punish any contractor of government establishments and
buildings which collapsed due to negligence in the killer
earthquake Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Rasoul Zargar, head of the Natural Disasters Headquarters of
the Interior Ministry, said that those who were found neglecting
the building codes and standards will be reprimanded.
</P>
<P>
The official made the statement while inspecting the
devastations caused by the quake of magnitude of 7.1 in east
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Zargar said that one of the causes behind the collapse of
government buildings in southern Khorasan province was that the
contractors of these buildings did not build them quake-resistant.
</P>
<P>
More than 15,500 houses were destroyed in Birjand and Qaen,
the epicenter of the earthquake which hit eastern Iran Saturday,
about 800 kilometers east of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has offered 20 percent stake of the shares of
three big state-run companies for sale in the stock exchange, the
English daily the Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The companies to go on the market are the Egyptian Iron and
Steel Company, the Sugar and the Integrated Industries Company
and Misr Aluminum Company.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 20.2 million shares will be put up for sale, with a
total value of 448 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and the United Arab Emirates have signed an
agreement on guaranteeing and protecting investment of the two
countries, the Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Economy and International Cooperation Nawal
el-Tatawi said after signing the agreement Monday that Egypt
provided a favorable atmosphere for investment projects.
</P>
<P>
Tatawi expressed the hope that the agreement would boost
economic and trade cooperation between the two countries.

12/05/97 19:38 GMT

