<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Nigeria Issue Press Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- China and Nigeria issued here today
a joint press communique on Chinese Premier Li Peng's successful
visit to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The press communique said that during the visit, Li Peng and
Nigerian Head of State Sani Abacha exchanged views on bialteral
ties and other issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders held talks in a friendly atmosphere of mutual
respect, which mirrored the good relations between the
governments and peoples of the two countries, said the
communique, adding that four documents of economic and trade
cooperation were signed between the two countries before the end
of Li's visit.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the two sides agreed that their two
countries have common interests in international affairs and they
are complementary to each other economically.
</P>
<P>
The two sides stressed that further strengthening
cooperation between China and Nigeria in various
areas conforms to the interests of the two countries, and they
shared the view that it is necessary to hold regular meetings of
the China-Nigeria Mixed Economic Committee, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The press communique said the leaders of the two countries
expressed their concern for the lack of security and instability
caused by civil wars and conflicts in the world and in Africa in
particular.
</P>
<P>
They reiterated that their two countries will adhere to the
aim and goals set in the U.N. charter and will strengthen
consultation and cooperation in their efforts to make the United
Nations more democratic and establish a world order based on
equality, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the two sides shared the view that
all countries, big or small, strong or weak and rich or poor, are
equal members of the international community and that relations
between countries should be based on the principle of fairness.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the two sides have taken note that
although tensions in international affairs have eased, hegemonism
and power politics still exist in relations between countries and
no change has been made in the unjust and unfair international
political and economic order.
</P>
<P>
The two sides expressed regret over the continued enlargement
of the gap between rich and poor countries, according to the
communique.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the two sides stressed that peace and
development remain the main tasks of governments and people of
various countries and that their two countries will continue to
cooperate to realize the goal of attaining peace and development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Premier conveyed regards for Abacha from Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and on behalf of Jiang Zemin extended an
invitation to the Nigerian head of state to visit China, said the
communique, adding that Abacha expressed his thanks and accepted
the invitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
