<HEADLINE> Turkey: No Withdrawal of Troops From Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish general has ruled out the
possibility of replacing the Turkish troops in northern Cyprus
with an international peacekeeping force, the semi-official
Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to northern Cyprus last weekend, Cevik Bir,
deputy Chief of Staff of the Turkish Armed Force, said that
Turkish troops were stationed there to safeguard peace and
stability.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that Turkey always supported a peaceful solution in
Cyprus, he said, "Greek and Turkish Cypriots should come together
and find a lasting solution, this should be the main goal."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish deputy chief was in northern Cyprus to meet Turkish
Cypriot leaders and to inspect the 30,000-strong Turkish troops
stationed on the divided island.
</P>
<P>
Bir said Turkey would continue its support to northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Turkey supported the U.N. Secretary General's efforts carried
out in this respect, but the Turkish government's guarantee for
northern Cyprus should be respected, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was split into two parts since 1974 when the Turkish
troops landed on the island to protect Turkish Cypriots following
an abortive coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece. A
self-claimed Turkish Cypriot republic was then founded in northern
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Greek Cypriots-dominated government is the
sole legal government of Cyprus while the Turkey-backed republic
is not recognized by the international community.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military leader also criticized the defense
cooperation between Greece and Cyprus, saying they were join hands
in "spoiling existing tranquility and stability on the island."
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Cyprus' anti-aircraft missile deal with Russian
early this year, Bir emphasized that this was not only a problem
of northern Cyprus and Turkey, but also a problem of the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had vowed to launch a military strike against Cypriot
targets following the announcement of the S-300 Russian missile
deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
