<HEADLINE> Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Officials in the U.S. embassy in
Tel Aviv were under Israeli intelligence agents' surveillance last
year, according to the latest edition of Time magazine published
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The weekly magazine quoted U.S. senior intelligence officials
as saying that U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk complained
privately that Israeli agents took "heavy-handed" measures for the
surveillance over U.S. officials in that country, including
following U.S. embassy employees in Tel Aviv and searching the
hotel rooms of visiting U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
The reports came amid an FBI investigation into whether a
senior U.S. government official had been providing sensitive
information to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Last week, The Washington Post reported that the probe was
launched in January after the National Security Agency intercepted
a secure communication between two members of the Mossad, Israel's
intelligence serve. In the communication, a Mossad officer in
Washington and a superior in Tel Aviv discussed to use a source
code-named "Mega" to obtain sensitive information from the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
The FBI believed that Mega they mentioned in their conversation
could be a U.S. government officials that has provided Israel
information in the past.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno confirmed that
the United States was investigating a possible leak of information
through the so-called "mega" to the Israeli intelligence service
Mossad.
</P>
<P>
Israel has denied to have been using a highly-placed U.S.
government source for confidential information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
