<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Chemical Group Seeks to Conquer Asia-Pacific Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The French chemical group
Rhone-Poulenc is seeking to conquer the Asian market with its
chemical, pharmaceutical, life science and fiber and polymer
products, said Jean-Marc Bruel, vice-chairman of the group, today.
</P>
<P>
He said that over the past 10 years, the Asia-Pacific region
has become the fourth largest market after Europe, North America,
and France itself, for the group's products, two thirds of which
are life science products, such as animal and plant health
promoters.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Asia-Pacific region took up 10 percent of the
global sale volume of Rhone-Poulenc group, which is the world's
seventh largest pharmaceutical and life science products group,
and its sale volume in the region increased by 20 percent from
1995 to 1996 to attain 1.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Rhone-Poulenc is now employing 8,700 people in the 43
production centers it is running in 19 Asia-Pacific countries and
territories, while its investment now amounts to 800 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Laguere, group senior vice president for international
affairs, said that since sustainable growth is an increasing
challenge to development today, Rhone-Poulenc is ready to help
Asia-Pacific countries protect their environment by providing
highly efficient insecticides, new catalysts for vehicles and
treatment of industrial wastes.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that by the year 2,000, around 1 billion
inhabitants in Asia-Pacific will be potential customers for
Rhone-Poulenc's products, as 90 percent of the group's products
have met the need of the region by now.
</P>
<P>
Rhone-Poulenc sold 220 million U.S. dollars of products in 1996
to China, a 75 percent increase over 1994, and it is running 12
industrial plants and having 15 business partners now in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The group estimates that China will develop into a regional
industrial base for Rhone-Poulenc and that half of its Chinese
sales will come from local production by 1999.
</P>
<P>
The group is opening a new multi-sector production center in
Pudong, Shanghai, which will focus on the production of specialty
chemicals and silicone products, and will be in charge of
distribution of the products across China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
