<HEADLINE> US to Provide Aid to Iranian Victims of Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States will provide
about 100,000 dollars in aid for the relief of victims of the
devastating earthquake that struck Iran during the weekend, the
State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, State Department spokesman Nicholas
Burns said that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright "has decided
that the United States will extend roughly 100,000 dollars in
emergency humanitarian assistance."
</P>
<P>
He noted that Iran and the United States have had disputes
with each other for many years, "but we don't have any arguments
with the people of Iran. The people of Iran obviously are in
need of support."
</P>
<P>
The United States is trying hard to organize an international
economic boycott of Iran aimed at strangling its development which
it hopes would lead to collapse of the Islamic government.
</P>
<P>
But critics of the U.S. policy would prefer a more flexible
approach. They would permit some business deals and try to
influence Iran to moderate its views. However, Republican Senator
Sam Brownback, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Near East
Subcommittee, is calling for a tougher policy toward Tehran.
</P>
