<HEADLINE> Thames Offers Free Leak Repair for Customers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, MAY 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's biggest water company is
offering a free leak repair service for its 7 million customers,
according to BBC TV's Panorama tonight.
</P>
<P>
Thames Water has pledged to repair damaged underground pipes
between the garden fence and front door at no charge.
</P>
<P>
The company, which has the worst seepage rate in the country,
agreed to provide the free service after being confronted with an
internal memo in which its engineers claimed such a move "was not
an option."
</P>
<P>
The document revealed that fixing every household leak would
save 7 million gallons a day and cost the multimillion-pound
company only 4.5 million pounds (7.2 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Thames, which is expected to make 368 million pounds (588.8
million US dollars) in pre-tax profits this year, loses nearly 40
percent of its supply in leaks, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Between 4 and 10 percent of the wastage occurs on the
customer's side of the stopcock.
</P>
<P>
The Thames offer will last until at least the autumn. Ian
Byatt, director general of the industry watchdog Ofwat, said some
companies were in danger of "cutting corners" in an attempt to
save costs.
</P>
<P>
Ofwat officials and many industry experts believe water
companies concentrate too much on building new reservoirs instead
of carrying out repairs on the existing infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
New Environment Minister Michael Meacher is expected to call
for free household leak repairs across the country and speedier
repairs to mains pipes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
