<HEADLINE> Jordan to Help UNRWA Procure Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today promised to campaign for
funds for Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with visiting United Nations Relief and Works
Agency (UNRWA) Commissioner-General Peter Hansen here, Prime
Minister Abdul Salkam Majali said his country will ask donor
countries to increase their financial assistance to the
organization.
</P>
<P>
Details of Jordan's support have not been disclosed yet.
</P>
<P>
In January, Hansen paid an official visit to Jordan, where
two-thirds of its population are Palestinians and some other
Palestinians are refugees.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner-general's January trip was also centered on
asking for financial aid for UNRWA, which was established in 1949
to deal specifically with the Palestinian refugee issues in
Jordan, Syria, Lebanon, the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
"The international community is faithful to UNRWA, but we are
not seeing enough increase of income because the Palestinian
refugee population is increasing and the cost of maintaining the
programs are increasing too. So we need a faster growth in our
income to finance programs," said Hansen during his last trip to
Amman.
</P>
<P>
Some 1 million Palestinians were made homeless during the First
Middles East War in 1948 when Israel annered part of the
Palestinian land. They are now in refugee camps in Jordan, Syria,
Lebanon and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. then set up the UNRWA, a sister agency to the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), to deal with the
Palestinian refugee issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
