<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Software Alliance Warns Egypt on IPR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will be subject to a range of
World Trade Organization (WTO) sanctions if it continues to fail to
protect intellectual property rights (IPR), said Egypt's largest
English business magazine.
</P>
<P>
The Business Monthly reported in its May issue that the WTO
message has been delivered recently at a conference organized by
the software industry group Business Software Alliance
International (BSA) here.
</P>
<P>
Brian McEachren, senior corporate attorney for Microsoft and a
vice-president of BSA International, joined by two other vice-
presidents, expressed discontent with the fact that piracy
consumes an estimated 80 percent of Egypt's 100 million
U.S. dollars a year software market.
</P>
<P>
"Our institution is getting worse, and nobody is taking any
action," Sherin el-Rayes, chairman of BSA Egypt, was quoted by the
English magazine as saying.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Supply and Trade Ahmed el-Goweili, who is
responsible for IPR protection in the country, had agreed to
resume the raids on software pirates, which he canceled under
pressure from businesses last summer.
</P>
<P>
But the raids have yet to resume, said el-Rayes, adding that
the BSA will wait until June before calling the latest government
initiative a failure.
</P>
<P>
Software industry executives say Egypt's industry will remain
underdeveloped until copyrights are protected, said the magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
