<HEADLINE> Draft Russia-Belarus Charter Almost Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The draft charter on integration due
to be signed by Russia and Belarus next week has been basically
agreed by both sides, although differences still remain, Russian
President Boris Yeltsin's press secretary said today.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Yastrzhembsky said two problems remained, although none
was of "any fundamental importance," and President Yeltsin had
sent a message to Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko that
he was satisfied with the work done to finalize the charter.
</P>
<P>
If negotiators failed to iron out these differences over the
next few days, the two presidents would try to find a common
approach to the problems during their meeting on May 23, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Russia-Belarus Charter is part of the Union Treaty signed
between the two countries on April 2 this year aimed at closer
integration.
</P>
<P>
The treaty provided for the setting up of supra-national bodies
and a timetable for the creation of a common market and monetary
union and joint transport and energy systems.
</P>
<P>
Details of proposals for the union were contained in the
separate charter which was put out for public debate. The deadline
for accepting proposals for consideration in the charter was May
10 and the final version is expected to be presented to the
presidents of both countries by May 15. They are due to meet to
sign the charter on May 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
