<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Still Uneligible for Emu Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, May 13 (Xinhua)-- Finance ministers of the European
Union have urged Sweden to cut its budget deficit to qualify for
membership of the single European currency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in Brussels yesterday, the ministers called on Sweden
and nine other EU countries to improve their finances to qualify
for EMU.
</P>
<P>
Only Luxembourg, Ireland, Denmark, Finland and the Netherlands
meet the requirements laid down in the EU's Maastricht Treaty on
monetary union.
</P>
<P>
Sweden is still on the list of countries whose present budget
deficits exceed 3 percent of GDP and is thus not eligible for
membership of the single European currency.
</P>
<P>
The government has signalled its intention to bring its budget
deficit down to 2.2 percent of GDP this year. But the EU has urged
Sweden to cut public spending further and eliminate its deficit by
1998. It has also called on the government to lower taxes for
households and companies to stimulate the economy and create
jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
