<HEADLINE> WEU to Set Up Military Committee; Boost EU, NATO Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The defense and foreign ministers of
the nine Western European Union (WEU) countries today decided to
set up a NATO-style military committee to advise the WEU's ruling
council and to strengthen relations with the European Union and
NATO.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also decided to increase of operational power of
the WEU which this year, for the first time in its 49-year
history, organized a major humanitarian mission (to Albania).
</P>
<P>
The new WEU military committee will organize meetings twice a
year for the chiefs of the armed forces of WEU members, and will
be represented by a permanent delegation selected from WEU
countries.
</P>
<P>
Following the NATO model, the military committee will serve as
military advisor to the WEU Council, the main political body of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
Agence France Presse quoted a diplomat as saying that the
committee would clarify and define the previously vague status of
military officers within the WEU.
</P>
<P>
The WEU, set up in 1948 to push forward European unity and help
guarantee European security and defense, comprises France,
Germany, Britain, Italy, Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg,
Spain and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
France and Germany want to integrate the WEU into the European
Union as its defense arm as part of the process of EU
institutional reform now being negotiated among EU countries, but
Britain is strongly opposed to the idea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
