<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Concerned About Drugs Sales on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
warned today that untried, ineffective or fake medicine could be sold
through the Internet because of a lack of control of advertising and
sales in electronic communications.
</P>
<P>
A resolution expressing concern over the issue and calling for
the careful evaluation of the effectiveness, safety and quality of
medical products, was adopted at the 50th World Health Assembly
being held here from May 5-14.
</P>
<P>
It said advertising, promotion and sales through the Internet
might result in uncontrolled across-the-border trade of medical
products or fraudulent imitations that may be unevaluated,
unapproved, unsafe or ineffective, or inappropriately used.
</P>
<P>
In most of the WHO's 191 members, medical products
require authorization prior to marketing, and are available only
on medical prescription.
</P>
<P>
The resolution called on the WHO's director-general to
collaborate with drug regulatory authorities and the medical
industry worldwide to see that medical products are adequately
evaluated before being marketed.
</P>
<P>
An ad hoc group under the WHO Drug Management and Policy
division will hold its first meeting next September to discuss the
sale of medical products on the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
