<HEADLINE> Chinese President Asks Nation to Learn from Disabled (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin has
called on the nation to learn from the disabled persons' spirit of
self-supporting and working hard.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also general secretary of the Chinese Communist Party
Central Committee, was speaking at a national meeting at the Great
Hall of the People here today to commend outstanding disabled
people.
</P>
<P>
The handicapped people constantly strive to become stronger as
well as to unite and help each other, the Chinese leader pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Deng Pufang, chairman of the China Disabled
Persons' Federation, delivered a report on how the disabled
learn to become self-reliant and work to help each other.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin and other Chinese leaders, including Qiao Shi, Li
Ruihuan, Zhu Rongji, Liu Huaqing and Hu Jintao, met and talked
with representatives of the outstanding disabled persons and
of those who have done much to help the disabled.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the disabled display the spirit of
self-respect, self-confidence and self-supporting that the
Chinese nation has developed for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
This kind of spirit has enabled the nation to make indelible
contributions to the human civilization, he said.
</P>
<P>
"To meet the challenge of the 21st century, to build the
motherland into a prosperous, democratic, civilized and modern
socialist country, the national spirit of striving to become
stronger must be constantly carried forward with great efforts," he
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the unusual contributions made by the disabled
are closely related to the nationwide campaign of helping them.
</P>
<P>
The campaign has embodied the Chinese nation's traditional
ethics of taking it as a pleasure to help others, and it should
be promoted by the society as a whole, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Ours is a socialist country. So, we must encourage the people
to understand, respect and care for each other by promoting
collectivism, thus creating an equal and fraternal social
environment marked by mutual help," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Asks Nation to Learn from Disabled (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang asked the general public to respect and help the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Chinese Communist Party's ultimate purpose is
to liberate humanity. Since the founding of New China in
1949 the fundamental political and economic conditions for the
protection of human rights have been attained.
</P>
<P>
The people's rights to subsistence and development have been
protected more and more effectively, he said, and remarkable
achievements have been made in helping and protecting the disabled.
</P>
<P>
The fact that millions of disabled persons have been
participating in social activities and national construction
proves the guarantee of universal, fair and real protection
of human rights in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that China has 60 million disabled people, and they
are related to one fifth of all Chinese families. Therefore, the
protection of the disabled is related to the people's immediate
interests, to the emancipation and development of productive forces,
and to social stability and unity.
</P>
<P>
So it is the duty of the Party and the government to do a good
job in this regard, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Party and the government have done a great
deal of work to protect the disabled. However, because the
country's overall economic and social development is at a low
stage, "we have encountered a lot of difficulties. It is a
long-term and arduous task to help the disabled," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He cited Beethoven as an example of a man who encouraged people
to challenge fate. Even after he became deaf, Beethoven composed
some of his best works.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that in Beethoven's time people could only combat
the fate in isolation. But in today's China the disabled can count
on receiving care from the Party, the government and the whole of
society.
</P>
<P>
So, they can compose even greater masterpieces, he
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
