<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Provides Aid to Iranian Quake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 13 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations office in Iran
announced here today that it has donated 810,000 U.S. dollars to
the victims of the killer earthquake in east Iran.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Information Center here said in a press release that
a U.N. team is visiting southern Khorasan province to assess the
extent of the damages caused by the strong quake.
</P>
<P>
The world body has already appealed to the international
community for assistance to the quake victims following a request
by the Iranian government, the information center said.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting here today, which was presided over by
U.N. Resident Coordinator Michael Schulenburg and attended by
heads of the U.N. agencies, the situation in the affected areas
as well as the extent of foreign aid were reviewed.
</P>
<P>
Schulenburg also briefed diplomats from donor countries on the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Many countries have already responded by contributing relief
materials for the quake victims, the release said.
</P>
<P>
An earthquake of 7.1 magnitude hit East Iran last Saturday,
killing about 4,000 people and injuring 6,000 others besides
the destruction of about 200 villages in the quake-ridden areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Keeps Leading Status at East Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese athletes continued their gold
medal hunting on the third day of the second East Asian Games on
Wednesday, collecting eight titles from swimming, gymnastics,
weightlifting, diving and badminton.
</P>
<P>
After three-day competitions, China had accumulated a total of 18
golds, beating their arch rivals Japan and South Korea to the second
and third.
</P>
<P>
Chinese gymnasts displayed their brilliant performance on the floor
and appratus, winning the men's and women's individual all-around
titles through Zhang Jinjing and Liu Xuan.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jinjing, all-around fourth-placer at the Atlanta Olympic
Games, overcame the injury to his stomach to collect 56.400 points for
the top honour, while teammate budding star Huang Xu finished second
on 55.450 with the bronze medal going to Lee Joo-hyung of South Korea
on 55.200.
</P>
<P>
"Zhang displayed his top forms in four out of the six events, he
deserves the gold medal as he finished successfully in the rings, the
pommel horse, the parallel bars and the horizontal bar with new
routines," said Qian Kui, team manager of the Chinese Gymnastic
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Zhang scored the event-high 9.650 points in the rings and the best
of 9.600 in the horizontal bar.
</P>
<P>
"Even before the last event of floor exercise, I was sure of
winning the gold medal as my chief rivals were in the distant places,"
said Zhang prior to the medal-awarding ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The women's gold and silver medals were all taken by the Chinese
entries as veteran Liu Xuan beat down injuries to her legs and kept
her top forms in all the four events.
</P>
<P>
Liu collected a total of 38.262 points for the top place, while
Meng Fei got the silver on 37.900 and the bronze medal was taken by
Olga Kojevnikova of Kazakhstan on 37.362.
</P>
<P>
On the weightlifting platform, the Chinese lifters continued their
crane-style performance with one world record and two gold medals.
</P>
<P>
Zou Feie, veteran in the Chinese team, set a world mark in the
snatch of women's 59-kg category, lifting 100 kilograms in her second
attemtpt, beating the pervious record by one kilogram.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese girl, champion at the 1994 World Championships, also
won the division with a total of 220 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Zou Feie, from Hunan Province, had predicted for the world record
and the gold. "I was sure before competition that I could set a world
mark in the snatch and take the gold if I lift to my best," she said.
</P>
<P>
Another gold medal for China in weightlifting was from Zhang Yong,
who beat Ibragim Samadov of kazakhstan in the men's 83-kg division.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yong had a total of 365 kilograms for the title, outlifting
Samadov by 10 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The day's other two gold medals in weightlifting went to Chen Jui
Lien of Chinese Taipei and Lee Kang Seok of South Korea, who won the
women's 64kg division and the men's 76-kg category respectively.
</P>
<P>
Chinese swimmers made a splash in the pool, winning two titles out
of five on offer.
</P>
<P>
After Fu Yong won the men's 200m backstroke with a games record
time of two minutes and 0.73 seconds, the Chinese quartet took the
women's 4x100 freestyle relay at three minutes 47.39 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Japanese swimmers notched up two golds through Miyaji Sachiko and
Nakamura Mai in the women's 400m freestyle and 100m backstroke events
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The only other gold medal in the swimming pool on the day went to
Serguei Borissenko of Kazakhstan, who won the men's 100m freestyle at
51.36 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Zhijia who awarded China the first gold medal from diving
Tuesday afternoon, made a double by winning the women's 3m springboard
event with a total of 533.16 points.
</P>
<P>
Her compatriot Deng Yong was second at 525.57 and Irina Vygouzova
of Kazakhstan, who took the 1m springboard on Monday, finished third
at 505.47.
</P>
<P>
South Korean athletes displayed a dominating performance on the
mat, taking five out of eight gold medals on offer from the
Greco-Roman style wrestling competitions.
</P>
<P>
Other three titles went to Japan and Kazakhstan, who had two and
one respectively.
</P>
<P>
The women's and men's team events in the badminton tournament were
split by China and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
In the soccer's round-robin games on Tuesday, South Korea
whitewashed China 7-0, Japan beat Mongolia 5-0, Kazakhstan beat Guam
4-1.
</P>
<P>
In the men's basketball preliminaries, Kazakhstan beat Japan 77-67,
China outplayed Mongolia 91-43 and South Korea defeated Chinese Taipei
72-62.
</P>
<P>
In the only women's basketball match of the day, South Korea
overpowered Japan 80-65.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's competitions will decide 18 gold medals from
gymnastics, soft tennis, swimming and diving. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-British Joint Venture to Make Aero Engine Turbine Blades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a new Sino-British
joint venture to make airplane engine turbine blades has started
in this capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an XRA Aerocomponents LTD., a joint venture between Xi'an
Aero Engine Corporation and the British Rolls-Royce Company, will
produce the most advanced turbine blades for airplane
engines for the British company, with technology provided by
the British partner.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and British companies will pump 30 million US
dollars -- 51 percent of it from the Chinese side and 49 percent
from the British side -- which will be used to buy sophisticated
production equipment and build advanced precision casting
workshops and mechanical processing workshops.
</P>
<P>
According to a schedule, the joint venture will produce and
deliver its first batch of products next March. It will chalk
up 13 million US dollars in sales by the year 2000 and 30
million US dollars by the year of 2005.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an Aero Engine Corporation is one of China's leading
research and manufacturing centers of aero engines and now has
16,000 employees, plus 7,000 sets of advanced equipment. The
company, as one of China's export-oriented enterprises, has so far
established long-term trade cooperation ties with a dozen
companies of world fame.
</P>
<P>
Roll-Royce, one of the world's leading manufacturers, has
produced the most advanced plane engines and has been producing
aero engines to be used in making of Boeing and McDonnell planes.
</P>
<P>
The British company has also participated in a project of China
Aerospace Industries Corporation to develop passenger planes each
with 100 seats.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an Aero Engine Corporation and Rolls-Royce Company began
their cooperation as early as middle 1970s. The Xi'an company has
so far undertaken more than 60 deals to produce by subcontracting
airplane components and has earned 30.94 million US dollars from such
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
