<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wine Imports Skyrocket in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Customs Office
reported a steep rise in the imports of wine in the first four
months of this year, with the amount topping 1.06 million liters,
valued at 1.22 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The amount of imported wine in the first four months of
Last year was merely 21,400 liters.
</P>
<P>
Local market investigators attributed the phenomenon to the
change in consumers' attitude toward the mild alcoholic drink and
the failure of local suppliers to meet the soaring demand,
especially for red wine.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China has over 110 wineries, including eight
Sino-foreign joint ventures. In 1994 the country turned out
184,000 tons and in 1996 the output stood at some 300,000 tons,
according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
However, the experts said, there is a big gap yet to be
filled between the demand and the supply in China, as the
country's per-capita wine consumption is only 0.3 liter, compared
with than the world's average of six liters and far less than the
figure of 110 liters in developed countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Establishment of Rural Co-op Banks Urged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has been
urged to consider the establishment of rural cooperative banks
that will be owned by the local people.
</P>
<P>
The suggestion has been made in Chipata, capital of East
province by Norman Chipakupaku, Executive Secretary of the
Chipata Chamber of Commerce and Industry, the Zambia News Agency
(ZANA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
ZANA quoted Chipakupaku as saying that the government should
restructure the Cooperative Bank so that small and medium-sized
entreprenuers who had not access to its loan schemes could benefit
from the establishment of rural cooperative banks.
</P>
<P>
Chipakupaku said the rural banks would determine their interest
rates to meet the needs of the small and medium-sized businessmen
who were currently unable to obtain loans from commercial banks
because of their prohibitive interest rates.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that shares of the proposed rural cooperative banks
should be floated on the Lusaka Stock Exchange so that they could be
bought by interested investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
