<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia for Effective Public Assistance Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, MAY 13 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is concerned
about the effectiveness of the public welfare assistance program and
has taken measures to reform it.
</P>
<P>
This was said by Community Development and Social Service Minister
Newstead Zimba while opening a public welfare assistance scheme
dissemination workshop here today.
</P>
<P>
Zimba admitted that the scheme, which was meant to cushion the
poor from the effects of the Structural Adjustment Program, has
not done as expected despite an injection of four billion Kwacha
(1,300 Kwacha equal one US dollar) since 1992.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was for that reason his ministry last year
undertook a detailed evaluation of the program and used the
results as the basis for initiating a nation-wide consultative
process at community, district and national levels to solicit
views on how the scheme could be reformed.
</P>
<P>
After a careful study, the ministry has found that the scheme
needed to be community-based for it to be effective and avoid being
highjacked by the "smart poor" as has already been evidenced.
</P>
<P>
The program also needed to be re-oriented so that it
reinforces existing support systems operating at the community
level meant to help the destitute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
