<HEADLINE> Mubarak Leaves for Morocco to Promote Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
left here today for Rabat to meet with Moroccan King Hassan II on
his second visit in two months to promote the Mideast peace
process and bilateral cooperation on all levels.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will discuss the Arab efforts to push
forward the Mideast peace process which has broken down since
Israeli construction of a new settlement in East Jerusalem in
March, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Hassan II will preside over the meetings of the
Egyptian-Moroccan Higher Committee, due to open Wednesday to
explore ways to enhance bilateral cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The committee's agenda includes the plan of establishing a
joint company for marketing their products and increasing the
number of visits made by businessmen to discuss the best
investment means.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda are talks on establishing specialized fairs
or commercial weeks for Egyptian products in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Discussions at the committee will also cover the possibility
of a free trade zone between the two countries, as was
recommended by the committee's last meeting in Cairo last September.
</P>
<P>
The joint higher committee, which was established in 1988
during Mubarak's visit to Morocco, convenes every six months with
a view to promoting bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Egypt and Morocco amounted to 50
million U.S. dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
