<HEADLINE> French Chemical Corporation to Double Investment in China in 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- France-based Elf Atochem, the
13th-largest chemical manufacturer in the world, today announced
to double its investment in China to 600 million US dollars by the
year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Elf Atochem's visiting Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Jacques
Puechal told the local press that the company has inked two deals
ahead of French President Jacques Chirac's official visit to
China.
</P>
<P>
The company obtained approval from the Chinese government on
May 9 to set up a holding company to oversee its businesses in the
country, one of the fastest-growing marketplaces for the company,
with a registered capital of 30 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Signed on May 6 was a contract to form a 20-million-US-dollar
joint venture in Wuhan, capital of Hubei Province in central China.
</P>
<P>
According to Puechal, some 15 more projects are still under
negotiation with relevant Chinese departments, with the investment
totalling 300 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2001 the company is expected to have an annual
turnover of 500 million US dollars in China, 2.5 times the 1996
figure. Its Chinese employees are to increase by four times over
the current figure to more than 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Since entering China in 1987 the company has formed four joint
ventures, carried out 10 cooperative projects in different
industrial development zones and transferred 17 items of
technology to Chinese partners.
</P>
<P>
The company has five representative offices in Beijing,
Guangzhou and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Elf Atochem last year posted a business turnover of 10.5 billion US
dollars worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
