<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier, Tanzanian President Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng and
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa today highly valued the
Sino-Tanzanian friendship and promised to join efforts to
accelerate mutually beneficial cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Having traveled six African countries, Li said, he was deeply
impressed by the rich resources of the African continent and by
the diligence of the African people.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, Africa is still at poverty and
underdevelopment, which are the result of the long-time
colonialism and the unjust and unequitable international order.
</P>
<P>
In such a situation "it is all the more necessary to establish
a new peaceful, stable, just and equitable international
political and economic order, so as to bring about peace and
development," Li Peng stated. As for differences and
disputes among the developing countries, they should be settled
through negotiation and consultation.
</P>
<P>
Li praised the Sino-Tanzanian cooperation as one of the
models of the South-South cooperation, citing frequent exchanges of
visits by leaders of the two countries, growing economic and
technological exchanges and increasing mutual understanding and
support in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed the hope that his trip to Tanzania, the last leg
of his 7-nation African tour, would help enance mutual
understanding and deepen the traditional friendship and that
specific ways of cooperation in broader areas in the new
international situation could be explored. During the current
trip, he has visited Seychelles, Zambian, Mozambique, Gabon,
Cameroun and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said Premier Li Peng's trip to Tanzania and other
African countries fully demonstrated the friendly sentiments of
the Chinese people towards the Tanzanian people. Mkapa shared Li
Peng's view on the establishment of a new international political
and economic order, saying Tanzania is ready to cooperate with
China on the international arena. Tanzania would unswervingly
uphold the "One China" policy, he noted. Mkapa also extended
congratulations to China on the resuming of exercising
sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Expounding necessity of the changes of economic cooperation in
both ways and content, Li said, the readjustment or reforms in
this regard is aimed at meeting the needs of the new situation and
at continuing expanding the cooperation. Such a cooperation should
be based on equality and mutual benefit, give free rein to each
side's advantages, and better supplement each other, thus producing
efficiency for both sides, Li stressed.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng stated that the Chinese government would support and
encourage the bilateral cooperation in diverse forms in such areas
as automobile assembling, textile, agriculture and mining.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said he welcomes Chinese enterprises to Tanzania, either
investing, running joint ventures and cooperative enterprises or
setting up wholly-owned firms. The joint ventures could
manufacture commodities oriented to eastern and southern
Africa as Tanzania wishes to become a bridge and gate of China's
economic exchanges with the regions, Mkapa said, adding that the
Tanzanian government would provide necessary gurantee by means of
legislation and the formulation of policies for enterprises of
both sides.
</P>
<P>
The famous Tanzania-Zambia railway has been playing an active
role in the economic development of the two countries, Li said.
And Li and Mkapa are of the identical view that China, Tanzania
and Zambia should strengthen cooperation in funding, renewing
equipment and improving management so as to make the artery
better serve the economic development.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Li Peng and Mkapa oversaw the signing of 3
agreements between the two countries, namely, the Agreement on
Sino-Tanzanian Economic and Technological Cooperation, the
Agreement on China Providing Exclusive Loans to the Tanzanian and
Zambian Governments for Tanzania-Zambia Railway, and the
Documents on China Providing Aid to the Zanzibar Government.
enditem

