<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Plans for Stronger Economic Growth, Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia's economy is projected
to grow 3.75 percent in 1997-1998 with the underlying inflation
rate remaining unchanged at 2.0 percent and unemployment rate
growing slightly to 8.75 percent, the federal government announced
tonight.
</P>
<P>
According to the federal budget submitted today by Federal
Treasurer Peter Costello to the parliament, the nation's economic
growth rate for the fiscal year 1997-1998 is forecast at 3.75
percent, from this year's 3.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The mid-year forecast for an underlying deficit in 1996-1997 of
8.5 billion Australian dollars narrowed to 6.9 billion (one
Australian dollar is equal to 0.78 U.S. dollars), while next
year's forecast widened by about 400 million Australian dollars to
3.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
Costello pointed to a turnaround in the budget position from a
10.3 billion Australian dollars deficit in 1995-1996 to a 1.6
billion Australian dollars surplus within the coalition
government's first parliamentary term.
</P>
<P>
The treasurer attributed the deficit reduction to spending
cuts, with public housing, pharmaceutical benefits and child care
the main target, and revenue increase, including large scale
privatization program, such as the sale of one-third of Telstra,
the nation's leading telecommunications company, or long-term
leases on major airports in Melbourne, Brisbane and Perth.
</P>
<P>
The government slashed foreign aid budget by about 26 million
Australian dollars to 1,430 million, down one percent on estimated
1996-1997 outlays, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Among others, it cut 561 million Australian dollars from
Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme and 200 million Australian dollars
over four years from public housing funding to states.
</P>
<P>
The treasurer also announced measures to encourage private
saving, boost small business, create jobs and help families by
providing assistance and savings rebate.
</P>
<P>
"With more saving we can finance more of our investment to grow
the economy faster and produce jobs," he said in a speech to the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The budget was criticized by the opposition party as doing
nothing for job creation.
</P>
<P>
Opposition treasury spokesman Careth Evans said, "There were
high expectations for job creation, industry and regional
initiatives, but they have been all dashed."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- For the first time in eight years, the Prime Ministers of
India and Pakistan met and held direct talks. Both called for
cuts in the military spending they described as ruinous for
their countries.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Yeltsin signed a peace treaty with his
Chechen counterpart, Aslan Maskhadov. Russia continued to insist
that Chechnya is formally part of the Russian federation and
pledged never to use or threaten to use force in relations with
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- NASA released the first returns from the upgraded Hubble
Space Telescope Monday. The scientists predicted that the new,
improved Hubble will soon eclipse the old one's achievements.
</P>
<P>
-- Opposition members of Mexico's Congress called on the ruling
party Monday to reopen a legislative probe into a government
agency reported to be under investigation on suspicion it was used
for drug trafficking and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The White House asked the Supreme Court to overturn a court
decision ordering administration lawyers to give the Whitewater
prosecutor notes of interviews with Hillary Clinton. 
