<HEADLINE> Carelessly Disposed Garbage Kills Wild Animals in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Indiscriminately disposed garbage
wounds at least one wild animal every week and has killed many of
them in Queen Elizabeth National Park in western Uganda, the New
Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ludwig Siefert, an expert from the Faculty of Veterinary
Medicine of Makerere University in Kampala, said that the most
dangerous rubbish is the hard objects such as cans and bottles that
cut feet of the animals looking for food or even kill them.
</P>
<P>
The most affected animal is warthog, an African pig with two tusks
and warts on its face.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan veterinary experts diagnosed a lung disease among the
warthogs and believed the disease could be tuberculosis infected
through food remians in dumped garbage, Siefert said.
</P>
<P>
He discribed the garbage abandoned by tourists as ''a disaster
to wild animals''.
</P>
<P>
Another wild animal susceptible to the dangerous remains is
mangoose, an African animal of Kangaroo family roaming in the area,
he added. enditem

