<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin's Interview with French Journalist (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the major issues concerning relations across the Taiwan
Straits, President Jiang said that the most important thing is
adherence to the "one China" principle internationally.
</P>
<P>
"That is, there is only one China in the world. The government
of the People's Republic of China is the sole legal government
representing the whole of China, and Taiwan is an inalienable part
of China," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
This is a fact that has been widely recognized by the United
Nations and the international community, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan question is an important question of principle that
has a bearing on China's sovereignty, territorial integrity and
the great cause of national reunification, the president said.
</P>
<P>
"To put an end to the separation between the two sides of the
Straits and realize the reunification of Taiwan and the mainland
is the common aspiration of all Chinese both in China and
overseas," he said. "It is also where the fundamental interests of
the Chinese nation lie. On such a question involving state
sovereignty the Chinese government has no room for any
compromise."
</P>
<P>
"Our basic policy on resolving the Taiwan question is
'peaceful reunification and `one country, two systems'," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"We always stand for a settlement of political differences
between the two sides and the realization of the reunification of
Taiwan and the mainland through political negotiations under
the 'one China' principle," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government and people have made unremitting efforts
to this end, he said, adding that on January 30, 1995, he
personally made an eight-point proposal for the peaceful
reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
"I proposed, among other things, that as the first step the two
sides can conduct negotiations on 'officially ending the state of
hostility between the two sides of the Straits under the principle
that there is only one China'," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"These proposals of ours are both reasonable and workable,
demonstrating our determination and sincerity about resolving the
Taiwan question on the 'one China' basis," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will, as always, resolutely uphold this principle and move
the cross-Straits relations further forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that whether or not cross-Straits relations can
improve and move forward steadily hinges on whether or not the
Taiwan authorities stick to the "one China" principle, truly
return to the "one China" position and stop their splittist
activities to create "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan" on
the international scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Interview With French Journalist (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As for the Tibet issue, President Jiang said that Tibet has
been part of China's territory since ancient times.
</P>
<P>
"Though there have been changes of central authorities, the
Tibet region has always been under the effective jurisdiction of
China's successive central governments," Jiang pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetans are members of the big family of the Chinese
nation, which is composed of 56 ethnic groups, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1959 the Dalai Lama and some elements of the then Tibetan
local government staged an armed rebellion in an attempt to
preserve the theocratic feudal serfdom that had existed in old
Tibet and to separate Tibet from the rest of China, Jiang said,
adding that the Dalai Lama fled the country after the rebellion
failed.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the Dalai Lama, with the support and
connivance of certain foreign forces, has clung to his position of
splitting the motherland and has never ceased his separatist
activities.
</P>
<P>
"He has sent agents into China's Tibetan-inhabited areas to
plot and instigate riots," Jiang said." At the same time, he has
tried to internationalize the question of Tibet by traveling
around the world begging for support."
</P>
<P>
Certain foreign forces have bestowed on him various laurels
while indulging in fabricating sensational lies about Tibet, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
"For us, we welcome visits to Tibet by foreigners, as then they
can see for themselves the real situation there," he went on to
say. "All those who go there will find a Tibet that is nothing
like the stories they have been told."
</P>
<P>
Thanks to support and assistance from the central government
and people all over the country, Tibet has, over the past few
decades, achieved economic growth, social progress and ethnic
harmony, Jiang said, noting that the people there live in peace
and contentment, enjoying steadily rising living standards and
guaranteed freedom of religion.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the current status of Sino-French
relations, President Jiang said that the bilateral relations
between the two countries indeed experienced certain setbacks in
the early 1990s, and this was "something we did not want to see".
</P>
<P>
He said that he himself visited France in September 1994, and
Premier Li Peng also paid an official visit last April.
</P>
<P>
"Both visits produced significant results in the political,
economic and trade areas, and enhanced our friendly cooperation in
all fields," Jiang said. "We view with joy and satisfaction the
sound growth of bilateral ties."
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming visit to China by President Chirac will be yet
another major event in Sino-French relations, he said, noting
that the maintenance of regular contacts between leaders of the
two countries is of great importance in that it helps deepen
mutual understanding, develop friendship, increase trust and
expand cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that the forthcoming visit by President Chirac
will further facilitate the all-round growth of Sino-French
relations," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
With today's world continuing to move toward multipolarity,
China and France -- both permanent members of the UN Security
Council -- are in the position to exert a major influence in
international affairs, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, to step up bilateral consultations and cooperation
and forge a long-term and stable relationship of friendship and
cooperation oriented to the 21st century will serve not only
the interests of our two countries but also the efforts to
establish a new Asia-Europe partnership as well as peace,
stability and development the world over," President Jiang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
