<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Ambassador to China Hails Chirac's Coming Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac's
forthcoming visit to China will be "one of extreme importance",
said French Ambassador to China Pierre Morel during a recent
exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The president hopes that his visit, the first by a French state
leader in 14 years, will touch upon all sectors since France
expects to be a co-operative partner of China on an overall scale,
Morel said.
</P>
<P>
France is ready for long-term cooperation with China in
different fields, such as politics, economy, technology, culture,
education, environmental protection, city construction, etc., he
said.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador reiterated that Chirac's visit will "strongly
promote" bilateral relations. "We hope the visit will push
bilateral ties to a new stage and make the co-operative
partnership between France and China more orderly and
systematically planned," he said.
</P>
<P>
The development of bilateral relations has proved that the
joint communique issued by the two governments on January 12,
1994, was well-prepared and well-drafted, he noted, adding that
the document has enabled both sides to carry out fruitful
co-operation and reach common understandings.
</P>
<P>
The two governments have exerted great efforts in making and
observing these decisions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"That doesn't mean that we hold the same views on all issues.
But when our opinions are different we hold constructive
dialogues candidly and calmly, and always respect each other, with a
view to deepening our mutual understanding," Morel said.
</P>
<P>
Both France and China are always trying to seek common ground
and opportunities for the development of both countries in both
the political and economic spheres, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth of bilateral ties over the past three years
shows that the two countries have successfully opened up a new
road in this regard, he added.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador revealed that President Chirac will also raise
the issue of Sino-European relations during his coming visit. "We
should make closer the relationship between France and the rest of
Europe and Asia, especially China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Morel pointed out that, as permanent members of the United
Nations Security Council, both France and China bear special
responsibilities, and should contribute more to the peace and
security of the world.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, France and China have increased their
consultations on important global issues, and have achieved
notable results and have deepened their mutual understanding, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
