<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto Accuses Parties of Violating Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto urged
today that leaders of the country's three political parties be
admonished for what he called "brutal acts" committed by their
supporters during election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
The president gave the instruction to Chairman of the Election
supervisory Committee Singgih when the latter reported to him the
campaign activities.
</P>
<P>
"We should uphold the campaign regulations," Singgih said,
adding that brutalities have increased since election campaign
started on April 27.
</P>
<P>
Singgih, who is also the attorney general, said 49 people have
died in the past 17 days.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the three parties -- the United Development Party
(PPP), the ruling Golkar party and the Indonesian Democratic Party
(PDI) -- "have already broken the campaign rules."
</P>
<P>
Their violations range from light to heavy, he added.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the three parties, he said, should be reprimanded
because they are responsible for their supporters' actions.
</P>
<P>
The three parties, which are preparing to contest the May 29
poll, will end their campaigns on May 23.
</P>
<P>
They will vie for 425 seats in the 500-seat House of
Representatives during the forthcoming election. The other 75
seats are reserved for the military, whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
In this year's campaign, the country is divided into three
groups of campaign areas where the three parties could conduct
their campaign activities in turn.
</P>
<P>
According to new election rules, motor parades and marches are
not allowed during the campaign. However, all the three parties
have violated the rules by showing their strength in the streets.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 124 million voters are expected to take part in the
general election, the sixth in the country since 1971.  
</P>
</TEXT>
