<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Gymnasts Finish 1-2 in Individual All-Arounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese gymnasts demonstrated their
world-class skills to finish one-two in both the men's and women's
individual all-around events at the second East Asian Games here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jinjing, all-around fourth-placer at the Atlanta Olympic
Games, overcame the injury to his stomach to collect 56.400 points for
the top honour, while teammate budding star Huang Xu finished second
on 55.450 with the bronze medal going to Lee Joo-hyung of South Korea
on 55.200.
</P>
<P>
"Zhang displayed his top forms in four out of the six events, he
deserves the gold medal as he finished successfully in the rings, the
pommel horse, the parallel bars and the horizontal bar with new
routines," said Qian Kui, team manager of the Chinese Gymnastic
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Zhang scored the most of 9.650 points in the rings and the best of
9.600 in the horizontal bar.
</P>
<P>
"Even before the last event of floor exercise, I was sure of
winning the gold medal as my chief rivals were in the distant places,"
said Zhang prior to the medal-awarding ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yufu, who finished atop the standing after the team event,
failed in both pommel horse and horizontal bar, finished in a distant
six place on 54.750 points with the day-high score of 9.700 in the
parallel bar.
</P>
<P>
"It did not surprise us when Lu suffered the blunts because he
tried the most difficult routines in the competition," said manager
Qian.
</P>
<P>
"Lu remains as our promising star since he is an all-around gymnast
with no weak event in the six apparatuses," the manager said.
</P>
<P>
The women's gold and silver medals were all taken by the Chinese
entries as veteran Liu Xuan beat down injuries to her legs and kept
her top forms in all the four events.
</P>
<P>
Liu collected a total of 38.262 points for the top place, while
Meng Fei got the silver on 37.900 and the bronze medal was taken by
Olga Kojevnikova of Kazakhstan on 37.362.
</P>
<P>
Kui Yuanyuan of China, who stood atop after the team event, failed
in her strong event of floor exercise to rank fourth with a total of
37.162 points.
</P>
<P>
Kui was the gold medalist in the floor exercise at the 1996 World
Championships in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
"Our athletes had dominating advantages over their peers in the
games which was being exploited to whet their prowess for the 1998
Asian Games and the 2000 Olympic Games," said Qian Kui.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Chinese gymnasts had swept all four gold medals in the
competitions with other 10 to be contested on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
