<HEADLINE> Stone Column to Commemorate Hong Kong's Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Construction of an
11.6-meter-high stone column officially started today at Sheung
Tsuen Park, Yuen Long of the New Territories, to commemorate Hong
Kong's handover to China at midnight on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the Pat Heung Rural Committee, the column will be
the first permanent building in Hong Kong in commemoration of the
handover.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of Pat Heung Rural Committee Philip Lai said that
members of the committee had voluntarily donated more than one
million HK dollars (about 128,000 U.S. dollars) for erecting the
column.
</P>
<P>
He said that the column will be finished in about one month,
and over 20,000 local residents will hold grand parties to
celebrate its completion.
</P>
<P>
Pat Heung is a place known for its strong resistance against
the British aggression in the 1890s, when more than 40 people from
the nearby villages laid down their lives in fighting the British
aggressors.
</P>
<P>
Lai said that the 26 villages in Pat Heung will organize a
series of celebration activities in the days before and after the
handover.  
</P>
</TEXT>
