<HEADLINE> HK Awards Water Works Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Work will start next week in Kwai
Chung on the Kowloon Peninsula for the construction of the
Butterfly Valley Primary Service Reservoir, according to the Water
Supplies Department.
</P>
<P>
A 297-million-HK-dollar (38.1 million U.S. dollars) contract
for the works was signed Monday by Director of Water Supplies Hu
Man-shiu and a representative of the contractor, Gammon-Kvaerner
Joint Venture.
</P>
<P>
"Upon completion in April 2000, the reservoir will have an
initial capacity of 40,000 cubic meters," Hu said.
</P>
<P>
"It has been designed to include provision for future expansion
in stages to an ultimate capacity of 200,000 cubic meters," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir will serve the current and projected housing and
industrial developments in Kowloon and the Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
The contract comprises all the civil, electrical and mechanical
works of the reservoir.
</P>
<P>
It is the first of three contracts awarded under the
"Additional Treatment and Water Transfer Facilities for the
Metropolitan Area and North-Eastern New Territories -- Stage I"
program, one of the largest projects undertaken by the Water
Supplies Department in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Ensuring adequate water supply for Hong Kong has always been
difficult because the territory lacks rivers, lakes and
substantial underground water sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
