<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Seminar on Year 2000 Problem Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Worrying about your computer of a
"sudden death" or malfunctioning at the turn of the century?
Racking your brain for possible disputes arising as one of the
consequences?
</P>
<P>
These were some of the topics at a one-day seminar here today.
The speakers urged solutions to be found before it was too late,
on the global issue of "The Year 2000 Problem" concerning the date
setting on computer systems worldwide.
</P>
<P>
But David Carse, deputy chief executive of the Hong Kong
Monetary Authority (HKMA), warned the audience that there would be
no "magic" solution.
</P>
<P>
The long-standing problem poses a terrifying picture that at
00:00:01 on the first day's morning of Year 2000, many computer
systems worldwide could malfunction or produce incorrect
information simply because the date has changed, according to
Carse.
</P>
<P>
And in a world so badly relying on computer systems, it could
cause wide-ranging implications for suppliers and customers, and
among the consequences could be business disruption or even
breakdown and, most probably, legal implications.
</P>
<P>
Time consuming and costly though, researchers worldwide who are
facing the exactly same deadline are competing for scarce
resources to fix the problem, Carse said.
</P>
<P>
And the HKMA has set for itself a target of having a Year 2000
compliant system in place by December 31, 1998, just one year
before that pressing deadline, he added.
</P>
<P>
The problem was caused by the fact that in the early days of
computing history, nobody thought the computer systems could be
used into the next millennium. And, on the economic side, a
two-digit system has been adopted in presenting the year to save
space in storage as external disk memory was expensive in the
early days for computers, according to Harenton Kam Nang Leung,
associate director and assistant professor at the Software
Technology Facilities Center in the Department of computing of the
Hong Kong Polytechnic University.
</P>
<P>
And one of the solutions will be to use Year 2000 compliant
products including programming languages, data management systems,
operating systems, system utilities, communication software,
embedded microcode and applications software, which were designed
to be used prior to, during, and after Year 2000, and will operate
without error relating to date data.
</P>
<P>
Some have already taken pre-cautions. HongKong Bank, for
example, started 10 years ago a policy that all new systems or
major changes in existing systems had to include Year 2000
compliance. So by now, almost all the bank's systems have been
Year 2000 compliant.
</P>
<P>
The bank has planned to make all the systems Year 2000
compliant by mid-1998, according to Bob Carlson, head of
Information Technology of the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking
Corporation Limited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
