<HEADLINE> Powerful Earthquake Injures Six in Southwestern Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- A powerful earthquake measuring 6.1
on the open ended Richter scale rocked Japan's main southwestern
island of Kyushu this afternoon, injuring at least six people, the
Metereological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that there was no threat of tsunami, or tidal
waves.
</P>
<P>
The quake, which struck at 2:38 P.M., injured at least six
people in northwest Kagoshima Prefecture and temporarily cut power
supplies at the Sendai city office, fire department officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Japan railway officials said trains on the Kagoshima, Nippo and
two other lines were suspended to allow workers to conduct damage
checks.
</P>
<P>
Members of the government's crisis Management Center
immediately gathered to assess the extent of the damage and discuss
countermeasures, a cabinet spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Kagoshima was shaken by a series of quakes in late March and
Early April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
