<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran: War Games in Gulf Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Iranian forces today claimed a
success for the first and second stages of a war game that started
in the Persian Gulf on May 11.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency reported that the first part of
the maneuvers consisted of commando and anti-commando operations
on land and sea, airlifting of personnel by helicopters and mine
sweeping operations.
</P>
<P>
At the second stage, the report said, participating forces
carried out various defense operations against possible attacks
with both conventional and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the third stage of the military
exercises, which includes attacks by Iranian marines on
hypothetical enemy positions and air raids on pre-determined
points, is to start soon.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,000 Iranian air and naval forces are taking part in
the joint military maneuvers code-named "Ya Hussein Shahid" in
the Persian Gulf and Sea of Oman.
</P>
<P>
The military exercises cover an area of 24,000 nautical
miles in south of the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the war games started in Jask port and
will extend to the second naval base of Bushehr, about 1,230
kilometers south of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Destroyers, helicopter gunships, missile launching vessels,
amphibious forces of the naval forces as well as the jet fighters
of the Air Force are engaged in the war games. The last stage of
the games will be carried out on May 17.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the maneuvers is to upgrade the combat capabilities
of the participating units and to apply various operational
strategies and new tactics to counter blitz assault of the
hypothetical enemy, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Islamic Revolution Guards Corp (IRGC) carried
out war games in an area covering 2,000 square kilometers in the
Persian Gulf water. Over 200,000 IRGC and Basij (volunteer) forces
took part in the maneuvers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin's Interview With French Journalist  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin had
an interview with a correspondent from French Magazine "Politique
Internationale" at Zhongnanhai, headquarter of the Communist Party
of China, on March 26 this year and answered his questions on the
political system in China, relations between the two sides of the
Taiwan Straits, the Tibet issue, and the Sino-French relations.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions about China's political system and major
difficulties between China and the western countries, Jiang said,
the form of a country's political system or political structure is
determined by its national conditions.
</P>
<P>
"These national conditions may include such things as the
country's politics, economy, culture, historical traditions, and
natural conditions, etc.,"
</P>
<P>
"The People's Republic of China is a socialist state. Our
Constitution provides that all state power belongs to the
people. The people's congresses are the organs through which the
people exercise state power. This is our fundamental political
system," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"We practice a system of multi-party cooperation and political
consultation under the leadership of the Communist Party as the
basic political structure of the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Regional autonomy is practiced in areas where people of
the ethnic groups live in concentrated communities,"
</P>
<P>
"Practice shows that our country's political system is
consistent with its national conditions as it has ensured the
fundamental political rights of the people, maintained the
national unity, solidarity of ethnic groups and social stability,"
Jiang continued.
</P>
<P>
"Even among the western countries, political structures differ
from one another with some practicing presidential republics while
others, parliamentary republics. It is thus obviously improper to
judge the political system of one country by that of another," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We will actively carry out political reform and strengthen our
building of socialist democracy and a legal system. In this
process, we will assimilate the outstanding achievements of other
countries while carrying forward the fine traditions of our own,"
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"Peace and development are the two main themes of the world
today. Maintaining global peace, enhancing friendship and
cooperation and promoting common development are the common desire
of all peoples," Jiang stressed.
</P>
<P>
"At present, worldwide stability and development are threatened
by such serious problems as poverty, unemployment, refugee flows,
crimes, population explosion, environmental degradation, drug
abuse and terrorism," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Though different in their national conditions, China and
western countries share broad common interests on a wide range of
major international issues," the Chinese president said.
</P>
<P>
"I am happy to see the improvement and expansion of China's
relations with them," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese Government and people stand ready to made a
contribution to the lofty cause of peace and development together
with the governments and peoples of all countries, including those
of western countries, on the basis of mutual respect, equality and
mutual benefit," Jiang said
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin's Interview with French Journalist (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang said that a sound and stable relationship between China
and Western countries accords with the aspirations and fundamental
interests of people in respective countries and is conducive to peace,
stability and prosperity the world over.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the two sides should "stand on higher ground and
take the long view", look upon their relations with a strategic,
world-oriented and 21st century-oriented approach and bear in mind
both their immediate and long-term interests.
</P>
<P>
"This requires that we properly handle the following
questions," he said:
</P>
<P>
"The first is how to treat our differences. I believe we should
work together to narrow our differences gradually on the basis of
mutual respect, equal dialogue and seeking common ground
while putting aside differences so as to preserve and advance our
common interests," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"We live in a colorful world of diversity. Such diversity has
made it possible for countries to interact and cooperate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Even in Western Europe, while actively promoting integration,
countries remain quite vocal about keeping their ethnic and
cultural distinctions.
</P>
<P>
The only right approach to the conduct of state-to-state
relations is to adhere to the Five Principles of Peaceful
Coexistence, recognize and face up to the differences in ideology,
social system and the level of economic and cultural
development. We must also make a break from the Cold War mentality
and the practice of the strong lording it over the weak, Jiang
noted.
</P>
<P>
The second is how to view China's development. China is the
largest developing country in the world. If China, as home to one
fifth of the world's population, can maintain political stability
and economic prosperity, it is in itself a great contribution to
world peace, stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Conversely, if China is unstable and stagnant, or if it should
bog down in prolonged poverty and backwardness, this will be
highly detrimental to world stability.
</P>
<P>
Now some Westerners deliberately exaggerate China's economic
strength and spread the "China threat" fallacy. This is totally
wrong. China's reform, opening-up and modernization programs need
an international environment of long-term peace and
stability. Even when China becomes more powerful, it will by no
means pose a threat to other countries, Jiang stressed.
</P>
<P>
The third is how to handle economic and trade cooperation. Such
cooperation between China and the Western countries is a mutually
beneficial one.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth in China has not only improved the living
standards of its own people, but also provided a fresh driving force
to world economic growth, together with greater business
opportunities for developed countries. China is a newly emerging
market with enormous potential, while the Western countries boast
advanced technology and abundant capital.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are highly complementary economically. The
discriminatory trade policies against China adopted by some
Western countries, while harming others, will in the end undermine
their own interests.
</P>
<P>
On China's entry to the WTO, Jiang said, "Our position is that
the WTO is incomplete without China's participation, and that
as China is a developing country it is inappropriate to ask it to
meet excessive demands."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
