<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Small Towns Boosting China's Rural Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Over 50,000 small towns in China
are pushing forward economic development and absorbing surplus
labor in the country's vast rural area.
</P>
<P>
According to latest official figures, more than 50,000
marketplaces have been set up in these urban areas, with a yearly
trading volume of over 450 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of rural enterprises are based in these small
towns, which have employed a total of 150 million rural laborers
and generate 60 percent of the gross domestic product in the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
The small towns have helped curb the influx of excessive rural
labor into cities. In the past five years, these small
communities have relocated about 60 million former farmers, and in
the future, seven to eight million rural people will be employed
in small towns and engaged in various industries.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Ministry of Construction told Xinhua that
China has been taking its own path in developing cities, based on
the principles of "strictly controlling the scale of large cities,
properly developing small cities, and actively expanding small
towns".
</P>
<P>
In some developed regions like the Pearl River Delta area, the
Yangtze River Delta, and Fujian, Zhejiang, Jiangsu, Shandong,
Liaoning, and Sichuan provinces where small towns have sprung up in
recent years, local farmers have introduced funds from other parts
of the country and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, these former farmers have been engaged in developing
urban facilities in these towns to narrow the gap in living
standards between urban residents and villagers.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, more than half of the families in small
towns have moved into new houses, with an average 17.18 m-living
space per capita, while 5.92 billion sq m-multi-story apartment
buildings have been put up in these towns, making up over 27
percent of the country's total coverage of residential buildings.
</P>
<P>
The mushrooming of these small urban places has bolstered the
construction of local infrastructure. According to official
figures, by the end of last year, China has over 3.09 million km
of rural roads, 69.8 percent of which have been paved.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, over 330 million rural people have access to
running water facilities, accounting for 33.9 percent of the
country's total rural population.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 percent of small towns and 74.8 percent of villages
have been electrified, while the afforestation rate in these tiny
cities have also been enhanced.
</P>
<P>
According to the country's blueprint for the development of its
small towns, China will modernize 10,000 small towns so as to
develop the local economy and absorb more excessive rural labor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
