<HEADLINE> Macao, Guangdong to Hold Police Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Police departments of Macao and South
China's Guangdong province will hold a meeting soon to discuss
major security issues, a top officer said here today.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Shaodong, deputy chief of the criminal investigation
division of the Guangdong Provincial Public Security Department,
said after a closed-door meeting with top Macao police officers
that the two sides reached a consensus in today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides agree that it is very necessary to hold a meeting
soon to discuss major security issues," he told reporters after
the 6th Guangdong-Macao Security Officers' Meeting. But he
declined to reveal when and where the meeting will be held.
</P>
<P>
The two sides had reviewed their cooperation since their last
meeting in Shenzhen City in November 1996, and concluded that
further exchange and cooperation are needed.
</P>
<P>
Issues discussed today included patrol on the sea, check of ID
cards and travel documents, improvement of work efficiency in
border posts, exchange of criminal investigation data, and joint
efforts in crackdown on illegal immigration, smuggling, drug
trafficking and triad crimes, according to Zheng.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation between the two sides is fruitful," he said. "If
requested, we will, as in the past, cooperate effectively (with
Macao police) in combating crimes and exchanging criminal data."
</P>
</TEXT>
