<HEADLINE> Number of Visitors Up in Hong Kong in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The number of visitors attending
Hong Kong's conventions, exhibitions, tourist incentives and
business meetings rose to almost 356,000 in 1996, or by 4.1
percent as compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Sally Brandon, manager of the Hong Kong Tourist Association
(HKTA), told reporters here today that the number of the events
grew by 39.3 percent in the same year, with a total of 3,030
recorded.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there was significant growth in both the number of
events and the number of visitors in the corporate meetings
sector, up by 16 percent and 59.1 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
HKTA believes one of reasons for this is the 1997 handover,
which may have spurred major international corporations to bring
their senior executives to Hong Kong to explore opportunities in
the territory. In addition, Hong Kong's position as the major
gateway to China has played an important role in this sector.
</P>
<P>
Another sector of the convention and incentive travel business
that showed good growth in 1996 was incentive movements. The
number of incentive trips to Hong Kong rose by 52 percent to 2,270
groups and the number of visitors on the trips increased by 12.4
percent to more than 100,500.
</P>
<P>
The convention and incentive travel sector remains an important
one for Hong Kong's tourism industry and its economy in general.
It is estimated that visitors traveling on this business tend to
stay twice as long as vacation visitors.
</P>
<P>
The number of association meetings held in Hong Kong rose by
9.7 percent to 294 last year, although the number of attendees
dropped by 17.3 percent to just over 57,000. HKTA attributes this
disparity mainly to the exceptionally large number of visitors
attending an unusually high number of mega association meetings in
1995.
</P>
<P>
The HKTA expects significant growth in this sector this year,
with a large number of association meetings already confirmed for
Hong Kong, in particular the Annual Meetings of the Boards of
Governors of World Bank Group and International Monetary Fund in
September.
</P>
<P>
The exhibitions sector showed a minor drop of 6.3 percent in
the number of events (59 in 1996) and 4 percent rise in the number
of visitors, bringing the total to some 177,000.
</P>
<P>
With the added capacity at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center due to come on line soon, the HKTA expects more
exhibition organizers to choose Hong Kong as their venue, and
forecasts that the exhibitions already staged on a regular basis
in Hong Kong will increase in size.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Celebrate HK's Return to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Macao has set a schedule of
celebrations around July 1 to mark Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
China's national flag will be flown over headquarters of mass
organizations, trade unions, shops, schools and residential
buildings in Macao on July 1, while firecrackers will be set off
at noon, according to the decision of a local celebration body
today.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Committee of the Macao Compatriots' Preparatory
Committee for the Celebration of Hong Kong's Return to the
Motherland also decided to hold a grand evening on July 1 to mark
the historic event.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based Central Nationalities Song and Dance Ensemble
will be invited to perform for three consecutive nights in Macao
from July 1, and major organizations and trade union offices will
be lit up overnight on June 30 and July 1.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of local artistic troupes will also stage performances
around July 1.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a special gift dedicated to the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, which is under design, will be presented on
behalf of the Executive Committee, said Tong Seng Chiu,
secretary-general of the Preparatory Committee.
</P>
<P>
"Preparatory groups for the celebration have been established
in many social bodies here," he said in a speech at a meeting of
the Executive Committee today. "We hope that various activities
around July 1 will make the celebrations animated, solemn, and in
a wide sphere."
</P>
<P>
Co-sponsored by eight leading organizations in Macao on April
1, the 182-people Preparatory Committee aims at good organization
of celebrations in the territory, thus laying a foundation for the
return of Macao in two and half years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a number of exhibitions, performances, lectures and
sports events with the theme of Hong Kong's return will be
launched soon this month and last through July 1 in Macao.
</P>
</TEXT>
