<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DNA Test in Pipeline to Detect Chlamydia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 13 (Xinhua) -- British scientists are
developing an inexpensive DNA test that can detect hidden
carriers of chlamydia, the most common sexually transmitted
disease, The Daily Telegraph reported today.
</P>
<P>
The British Wellcome Trust has awarded 1.7 million pounds
(about 2.7 million U.S. dollars) to the project, led by Dr
Helen Lee at Cambridge University.
</P>
<P>
Dr Lee said that the "dipstick" test relied on detecting the
organism's genetic code.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to develop an inexpensive test in a format so
simple that it works in the same way as a pregnancy test," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Symptoms of infection are minor and often disappear
without treatment. But untreated, the disease will continue
to do damage internally and can lead to infertility in
women.
</P>
<P>
In England, about 30 percent of men and 70 percent of women are
infected by chlamydia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
