<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Combating Desertification A Strategic Task For China, Vice Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Combating desertification will
remain an arduous challenge and will be a long-term task which
requires sustained efforts, Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun said today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made this remark at the opening ceremony of the Asian
Ministerial Conference on the Implementation of UN Convention to
Combat Desertification (UNCCD).
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Asia is one of the regions in the world
most severely affected by desertification, and that the
conference, a major initiative taken by Asian countries, will help
to develop positive regional cooperation in Asia so as to combat
desertification hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
He said that desertification has hindered the social and
economic development and the improvement of people's living
standard in some areas, and, "in other areas most severely
effected by desertification, the problem of food and shelter for
local residents remains unsolved."
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey, the total area of desertified
land in China is 2.622 million sq km, 27.3 percent of the
country's total land mass.
</P>
<P>
"Combating desertification in China is a must not only for
sustainable social and economic development within the country,
but also for improvement of the global environment," said the
Vice-Premier.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government is willing to develop broad cooperation
and exchanges with other Asian countries so as to make due
contributions to the global cause of combating desertification,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Vice-Premier, as a basic state policy, the
Chinese government has incorporated anti-desertification efforts
into plans for national economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
"The National Program to Combat Desertification and the `Three
North' Shelterbelt Program have brought more than 16 million
hectares of farmland and some 10 million hectares of rangeland
under effective protection," he told the 160 participants from 43
Asian countries and 18 governmental and non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
"Now 795 counties in plain areas have met the standards for
afforestation and the forest cover in China has risen from 8
percent in the early years after the founding of New China to
13.92 percent at present," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Conference is being jointly sponsored by the Chinese
government and the secretariat of UNCCD. Xu Youfang, Minister of
Forestry, chaired today's opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The conference will focus on the discussion of combating
desertification measures and the formulation of a common action
plan for Asian countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
