<HEADLINE> 7th Arab Parliamentary Union Opens in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The 7th Arab Parliamentary Union
(APU) Conference opened here today, with a call to enhance Arab
solidarity and establish a powerful economic grouping.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to enhance Arab economic cooperation," Arab
League Secretary General Esmat Abdel Meguid told the APU opening
session.
</P>
<P>
In this respect, he called for the creation of an Arab free
trade zone as the proper introduction towards the establishment of
an Arab economic bloc.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries have agreed to set up a free trade zone
within ten years starting from January 1998 as the first step to
create a common Arab market.
</P>
<P>
He said the APU can play a vital role in the activation and
strengthening of Arab joint action.
</P>
<P>
Following Meguid's address to the opening session, chaired by
Moroccan Parliament Speaker Galal el Said, Egyptian People
Assembly Speaker Fathi Sorour read out President Hosni Mubarak's
speech.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak called for an Arab collective spirit, a unified stand
and a clear-cut vision that would be able to overcome the global
and regional challenges.
</P>
<P>
Sorour, who was elected new APU chairman Monday, said that an
Arab solidarity and an Arab common market, two major topics tabled
on the conference' agenda, were the basic principles that will
make the Arab dream come true.
</P>
<P>
"Solidarity and a common market are linked, there can be no
market without solidarity and no effective solidarity without
economic cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also described the Arab unification as "the vital instrument
to stop Israel from breaching international law."
</P>
<P>
Altogether 17 top Arab lawmakers and their legislative
delegations take part in the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
