<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SSE Tightens Stock Market Supervision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Stock Exchange (SSE)
will spend three million US dollars upgrading its market
supervision system and develop personnel, said a SSE official
today.
</P>
<P>
The SSE is determined to function as a front line supervisor of
the stock market, after the stock exchange moves into the new
Shanghai Securities Exchange Building in the Pudong New Area this
July, according to Lu Wenshan, deputy director of the SSE's
Legal Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
Tight controls also await the securities companies, since the
SSE will unveil new systems to prompt the firms to submit
financial reports to the stock exchange and standardize the
inspection of securities companies, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that all these moves are designed and taken to meet the
expansion demand of the stock market, and out of the need to
protect the public investors.
</P>
<P>
"As a front line supervisor of the stock market, the SSE not
only organizes and keeps close watch on the stock trading, it also
supervises the listed companies and SSE members to ensure 'open,
fair and just' trading in the market and thereby a standardized
operation of the stock market," said Lu.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Stock Exchange set up its supervision division in
early 1995, to concentrate its once-scattered supervisory forces
in the wake of an accelerated expansion of the stock market. The
division consists of three departments: market monitoring,
surveillance, and legal affairs.
</P>
<P>
An in-time market surveillance system also went into operation
early last year, enabling the stock exchange to have timely
knowledge of any abnormal movements in the stock prices and
thereby reduce investment risks as early as possible by
discovering and stemming market irregularities.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the progress already made, Lu Wenshan said his
stock exchange would spare no effort to learn from its overseas
counterparts, so as to absorb their experience in market
supervision and advanced stock trading and surveillance technology.
</P>
<P>
"The supervision of the stock market is a long-term task and
our goal is to become a world-class stock exchange," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
