<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Flaring Increases in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The rate of gas flaring has shot up
to 77 percent of the total production following drop in the
volume of gas utilized in Nigeria, the "Guardian" newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said out of an estimated daily gas production of
3.8 billion standard cubic feet in the first quarter of this
year, only 20 percent were used by local industries or
re-injected by oil companies.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, gas flaring consumed 75 percent of the total
production, causing a daily loss of 433.5 million Naira, or 5.1
million U.S. Dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources attributed the drop in gas utilization to
decline in intake for its thermal stations by the National
Electric Power Authority, the sole biggest user of the country's
rich natural gas resources.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has set the year 2010 as the deadline
for the elimination of gas flaring, for which it has increased
the penalty for flaring from two kobo (100 kobos equal to one
Naira) to 50 kobo per thousand cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
In February this year alone, a total of 117 oil fields were
fined 4.83 million Naira (about 57, Dollars) for flaring, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
