<HEADLINE> Jordan Dispatches Relief Supplies to Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 13 (Xinhua) - A Jordanian transport plane left here
this morning for Tehran, the capital of Iran, carrying relief
supplies to the victims of the earthquake which hit eastern Iran
Saturday, killing as many as 2,500 people.
</P>
<P>
The plane carried tents, blankets, medical equipment, medicine
and food supplies collected by Jordan's Ministry of Health and
private pharmaceutical companies, according to a statement
released Monday by the Jordan Hashmite Charity Organization
(JHCO).
</P>
<P>
After the earthquake, King Hussein of Jordan sent a cable of
condolences to Iranian President Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani,
expressing the Jordanian people's grief over the casualties
caused by the earthquake.
</P>
<P>
Later, Crown Prince Hassan also sent a cable of condolences to
the president, requesting permission to send the relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
The Saturday's earthquake measuring 7.1 on the Richter scale
is considered the worst in Iran since 1990 when a 7.3-degree
quake claimed 40,000 lives in northern Iran. 
</P>
