<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKFE, NYMEX to Be Electronically Linked Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Futures Exchange
(HKFE) and New York Mercantile Exchange (NYMEX) will begin an
electronic trading link next month.
</P>
<P>
The link, which was agreed upon in September 1996, will provide
HKFE members with direct access to NYMEX products, including crude
oil, gold, silver, copper, heating oil, gasoline, natural gas,
propane and electricity, during the hours they are electronically
traded.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release jointly issued by the two bodies,
NYMEX access electronic trading terminals have been installed in
Hong Kong in preparation for the link, which starts with the June
13 trading session -- beginning at 4 p.m. June 12 in New York and
4 a.m. June 13 in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
NYMEX President Patrick Thompson said, "We are delighted to
forge this link, which will enhance risk management and hedging
opportunities in the Asia Pacific by providing it with ready
access to the world's largest precious metals and energy markets
through experienced local brokers."
</P>
<P>
"From our perspective, greater involvement from this key global
business center will increase the liquidity and price transparency
of our products during after-hours trading," he added.
</P>
<P>
HKFE Chief Executive Officer Ivers Riley described the link as
"representing the initial phrase of a long term relationship which
is likely to result in a series of NYMEX-HKFE jointly sponsored
contracts tailored to the needs of the Asia Pacific region."
</P>
<P>
He said: "This important first step will provide HKFE members
and their customers with electronic access to important and useful
NYMEX markets during our prime trading hours."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
