<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Forges Strong Economic Ties with Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese entrepreneurs are eyeing
Latin American markets for new destinations for trade and
investment, according to a recent symposium held here, "China
Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese companies should spare no effort to realize
localization -- to integrate production and sales," Dai
Yunlong, director-general of the American and Oceania Affairs
Department of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Co-operation (Moftec) said at the symposium Monday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed entity will be temporarily named " China and Latin
America Economic and Trade Development Co." aimed at foreign
trade, investment, exhibition organization and consultancy.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank predicted that the overall economic growth rate
of Latin America would hit 4.5 percent this year, higher than the
3 percent last year, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China exported 3.12 billion US dollars in machinery
and electrical products, textiles, chemical products and
pharmaceuticals to Latin America countries, down 0.8 percent from
that in 1995.
</P>
<P>
China also imported 3.6 billion US dollars in such goods as
iron ore, copper, rolled steel, crude oil, wool and sugar -- up
21.6 percent from that in 1995, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, Chinese entrepreneurs have launched about 160
wholly-owned and joint-venture efforts in 24 Latin American
countries, bringing total investment to 300 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"But great potential still exists -- and we need to tap the
huge market further in view of long-term economic co-operation,"
said Dai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
