<HEADLINE> UN Probes Ghaddafi's Visits to Niger, Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations (UN) Sanctions
Committee has launched a probe into Libyan leader Colonel Mummar
Ghaddafi's recent visits to Niger Republic and Nigeria to
ascertain if he has violated the UN air sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The "Vanguard" newspaper today quoted the United States' State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns as announcing the
investigation on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Burns stated that the UN will also probe the Nigerien and
Nigerian governments to determine the extent of their involvement
in Ghaddafi's trip.
</P>
<P>
The UN imposed an air embargo on Libya in 1992 for its
refusing to extradite to the U.S. or Britain two Libyans
suspected to have been involved in the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am
aircraft over Lockherbie in Scotland, which killed 269 people.
</P>
<P>
Ghaddafi, however, flew into Niger Republic and Nigeria last
week for official visits aboard a Libyan Airlines Boeing 727. His
fleet also included several other Libyan aircrafts conveying
government officials and security men. 
</P>
</TEXT>
