<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Former U.S. President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-U.S. relations are facing
a good chance of further enhancement, Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with visiting former U.S. President George Bush
and his wife here this morning, Jiang said since the beginning of
this year, the bilateral relationship has maintained a trend of
improvement, as the high-level contacts and exchange of visits
have continued to increase.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed Bush to visit China again, saying he appreciated
Bush's years of efforts to support the progress of the
Sino-U.S. relations and to promote bilateral exchanges in various
fields.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the history of the Sino-U.S. ties has shown that so
long as both sides earnestly abide by the three joint communiques
between the two countries, are far-sighted and oriented toward the
21st century, always grasp the common interests, properly handle
problems in the bilateral ties, especially the Taiwan issue, "We
thus would be able to continue to overcome difficulties and to
push our relationship forward on a long-term and stable basis."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese President hoped that Bush would continue to play
active role in promoting the healthy and stable development of the
Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Bush said that he has, as always, regarded the
U.S.-China relationship as the most important state-to-state
relationship in the world, but this relationship has often been
disturbed by various factors.
</P>
<P>
He noted that people should abandon their prejudice and see
clearly that a good relationship between the two countries are in
the fundamental interests of the people of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the bilateral ties will continue to be
improved and developed.
</P>
<P>
Bush extended welcome to Jiang's forthcoming state visit to the
U.S. this fall and wished the visit a complete success.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Jiang also briefed Bush on the Chinese
government's principled stand on the Hong Kong issue: "One
country, two systems; Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong; a high
degree of autonomy".
</P>
<P>
Bush said he believed that a smooth transition will be realized
in Hong Kong which in return will maintain its prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting was Liu Shuqing, president of the
Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
