<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reorganization Makes Industrial Giant More Competitive (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 13 (Xinhua) -- State-owned enterprises in
northeast China's Liaoning Province are making unprecedented
efforts in industrial reorganization.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has 1,426 large-and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises, or one tenth of the national total. They have a
combined fixed assets worth more than 360 billion yuan (43.37
billion US dollars). But, half of these enterprises had run at a
loss.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has picked out petroleum, metallurgy,
machinery, and electronics as the pillar industries in the four
years running up to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Thirtyeight state-owned enterprises, including the Anshan Iron
and Steel Company and the Panjin Ethylene Works, have been chosen
as the pace-setters. Some 140 billion yuan of investment will be
allocated to build 200 key projects in near future.
</P>
<P>
Over 320 industrial firms, including approximately 100 large or
medium-sized state-owned ones, declared bankruptcy, which reduced
the rate of assets and liabilities to 8.8 percent, a historical
low.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 25 competitive large state-owned firms have
displayed their abilities in an aggressive manner. They listed on
domestic stocks exchanges last year, pooling a total fund of three
billion yuan (361.45 million US dollars). The Liaoning-based stock
group is considered a "dark horse" on the Shanghai and Shenzhen
stocks exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Urged to Spend More on Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to catch up with its
neighbors in terms of economic development, the Philippine
government must step up its efforts to develop infrastructure
projects, the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
This recommendation was made by Gilbert Garchitorena, an
economist at the Institute for Economic Policy Research in Manila
after he noted that the Philippines has long lagged behind its
neighbors in economic growth because of poor infrastructures, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported earlier that the Philippines had the
lowest expenses on infrastructure in Asia, spending only two
percent of the gross national product (GNP) while the average
figure in Southeast Asia stands at seven percent of GNP.)
</P>
<P>
This deficiency in infrastructure facilities had not only
stunted growth but also discouraged a number of foreign investors
from driving down their stakes in the Philippines, Garchitorena
said in a research paper.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Philippine government should expand its
expenses on infrastructure construction while relying on the
private sector for infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, private spending on infrastructure began overtaking
public expenses in the country, he said. In the first half of 1996
alone, private investments accounted for 65.3 percent of the total
gross value in infrastructure construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
