<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reorganization Makes Industrial Giant More Competitive  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhao Xinliang, director of the Liaoning Provincial Planning
Commission, recently revealed that the market value of stocks
floated by local state-owned enterprises is expected to reach five
billion yuan by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Anshan Iron and Steel Company, Panjin Ethylene Work and two
other state-owned firms are to issue the H shares on the Hong Kong
Stock Exchange by June. The stock on the Shenyang-Dalian
Expressway is making final preparations for the listing in Hong
Kong, Zhao added.
</P>
<P>
During the province-wide reform, some state-owned enterprises
have joined hands to form 32 conglomerates in a bid to win a
bigger market share.
</P>
<P>
The Northeast Nonferrous Metal Group, which comprises a dozen
copper manufacturers, has developed into the largest nonferrous
firm in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The majority of Liaoning's 29,000 industrial firms are smaller
ones. To help them gear to the market economy, the provincial
government has introduced the share-holding system in 80 percent
of the medium and small enterprises.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the gross domestic product of Liaoning registered
a 8.6 percent rise to hit 315 billion yuan (37.95 billion US
dollars) in 1996. Its pre-tax revenue soared to some 40 billion
yuan (4.8 billion US dollars), 14 percent up from the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese economists deem that the industrial revolution in
Liaoning is an inevitable trend in building a socialist
market-oriented economy in China. The move will make this
traditional heavy industrial base even more competitive on both
domestic and international markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Quarterly Financial Situation Stable: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- China's financial situation was
stable in the first quarter of this year as the money supply
slowed down and foreign exchange reserves expanded continuously.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly supply of broad money (M2), cash plus all sorts
of deposits, was up 21.1 percent over a year ago, which was 4.2
percentage points down from the end of last year, according to
latest statistics of the the People's Bank of China, the central
bank.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the slowdown in the money supply indicated a
further easing of inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that the quarterly supply of narrow
money (M1), cash plus demand deposits of enterprises, grew 18.4
percent over a year ago while that of cash was up 13.6 percent, a
rise of two percentage points over the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said that China's hard currency reserves
continued to grow between January and March whereas the value of
the local Renminbi (RMB) yuan was stable.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March, China's foreign exchange reserves reached
112.06 billion US dollars, up 7.03 billion US dollars from the end
of 1996. The yuan was quoted at around 8.29 against the US dollar
at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Savings deposits of Chinese residents grew steadily in the
first three months of this year despite a bullish stock market and
a large issue of treasury bonds, the central bank noted.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding savings deposits were up 23.7 percent on a yearly
basis in the first three months to 4155.68 billion yuan (about 500
billion US dollars) by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Total bank loans during the January-March period rose an
annualized 21.1 percent to 158.5 billion yuan, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Overall, China's financial situation was stable in the first
quarter of this year, which guaranteed an adequately rapid
economic growth under a low inflation rate, the central bank
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
