<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Sales Drop in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The sales of new motor vehicles in
Kenya fell by four percent to 3,056 units in the first quarter of
this year amid a general downturn of the market as the general
elections approach and the effects of a recent drought.
</P>
<P>
The figure stood at 3,208 in the same period of last year,
according to the latest survey by the Kenya Motors Industry
Association.
</P>
<P>
However, the drop is modest and may reverse after the
elections if prices continue to remain steady, local experts
said.
</P>
<P>
"People tend to adopt a wait-and-see attitude and things are
likely to improve after they are certain of what to expect,"said
local expert Gavin Bennert.
</P>
<P>
New car sales dropped by a staggering 80 percent in the
1992-1993 period, recording the biggest decline in the industry
recently.
</P>
<P>
Between January and March, the Isuzu range led in the number
of units sold in the eastern African country with 475 vehicles,
followed by Toyota, 465, Nissan, 448 and Mitsubishi, 262.
</P>
<P>
Peugeot, Mercedes, Land-Rover and Mazda also sold more than
100 units respectively in Kenya in the period.
</P>
<P>
A total of 12,654 new vehicles were sold in Kenya last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
