<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian to Maintain Ban on Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has said it will maintain
the ban on ivory trade despite calls for its review by some
countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted deputy minister Fidelis Mando as
saying here Monday that Zambia will not side with Zimbabwe during
the meeting of the Convention on Internationnal Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES) to be held next month in Harare
because its elephant population is still threatened.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has benefited from the CITES ban on ivory trade imposed
eight years ago and managed to bring the animal numbers to
appreciable levels, but this is far from the original, said
Mando.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Botswana and Namibia are among the countries
favoring resuming limited international trade in ivory on the
ground that they have too many elephants and the limited ivory
trade can promote the conservation of the animal.
</P>
<P>
The CITES meeting will review the ban and consider placing the
elephant and rhino under appendix two to allow for restricted
trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
