<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Meeting on Fast Reactors Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The 30th Annual Meeting of the
International Working Group on Fast Reactors sponsored by the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) was held here today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has drawn the participation of experts and
officials from France, Germany, Brazil, India, Japan, the Republic
of Korea, Sweden, Russia, Britain, the Republic of Kazakhstan, and
China.
</P>
<P>
Mr.A.Rinejski, a senior IAEA official, said in the opening
speech that through nearly 50 years of development, fast
reactor technology has undergone scientific feasibility
study and engineering feasibility study. It will soon go into
global commercial utilization, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rinejski noted it is of great importance to develop fast
reactors as means of the world's energy supply, for it will
sharply raise the utilization rate of the rare nuclear fuel --
uranium, from around one percent by the existing thermal neutron
reactors to 70 percent in the new fast reactors.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu Mi, chief engineer of China's Fast Reactor
Research Center and the executive chairman of the current meeting,
China is a populous country which is short in energy supply. China
will give priority to developing fast reactor power plants amid
its drive to launch large-scale nuclear power construction, for
they are believed to be more efficient and safer and with a higher
utilization rate of uranium.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China plans to complete its first fast neutron
reactor power plant by the turn of the century, in order to meet
its increasing energy needs.
</P>
<P>
The reactor, the state's largest high-tech energy project, will
develop a thermal power of 65 MW and an electrical power of 20
MW, providing the technical basis for the country's first
commercial fast reactor power plant at the beginning of the next
century.
</P>
<P>
According to IAEA sources, there are 20 fast reactors worldwide
which are either completed or under construction, including eight
operational ones.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day meeting, experts from various countries will
exchange views on the latest development of fast reactors in their
countries, and coordinate technological cooperation between them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Biggest Port Fights Wayward Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's largest port city of
Mombasa has launched a crackdown on unscrupulous clearing and
forwarding firms holding un-canceled transit insurance bonds
worth million of Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Heads of such companies were questioned by Mombasa's customs
authorities on Monday, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The customs officials also scrutinized documents and made
random checks at several warehouses suspected to be storing cargo
in transit and other consignments for domestic use.
</P>
<P>
Most of the un-canceled bonds which date up to two years back
involve textiles, tires, sugar, shoes, electronics and rice --
which were said to be in transit to the neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Commissioner of Customs and Excise Samuel Chebii was
reportedly to fly to Mombasa today to monitor the crackdown
operation.
</P>
<P>
He was also expected to discuss with customs officers over how
to deal with more than 14,000 tons of sugar which is dubbed
"transit cargo" and being discharged at the Mombasa port.
</P>
<P>
Another 22,000 tons of sugar are stranded at the port because
their importers cannot meet new stringent regulations introduced
by the Kenya Revenue Authority last month to curb the diversion
of sugar in transit.
</P>
<P>
The regulation requires an importer or his agents to deposit
with the Customs a cash guarantee equivalent to the total value
of the cargo before the cargo is allowed to leave the port.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
