<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Settlers Rebuild Illegal Settlement Near </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Ten families of Jewish settlers
moved overnight into an illegal settlement on a hilltop near the
West Bank city of Nablus, which was evacuated by Israeli police last
week.
</P>
<P>
The settlers, who came from the nearby Yitzhar settlement in
south of Nablus, moved into tents and makeshift houses on the
hilltop, where three illegal buildings were demolished by the
police last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police set up an encampment near the hilltop to
monitor the situation and refuse to allow any building materials
to be taken there or permanent structures to be built. But they
did not intervene when more settlers moved onto the hilltop.
</P>
<P>
Four policemen and four settlers were injured last Tuesday when
about 200 policemen, army soldiers and government officials
carried out the evacuation of 30 settlers from the
hilltop. Twenty-five settlers were arrested in clashes with the
policemen when they tried to prevent the police from demolishing
the illegal houses.
</P>
<P>
The evacuation was a good gesture made by Israeli government to
the Palestinians ahead of the meeting last Tuesday between
President Ezer Weizman and Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat and the visit by U.S. peace envoy Dennis
Ross on a mediation mission to revive the stalled peace talks.
</P>
<P>
However, the move came under strong criticism by right-wing
ministers within the government, who demanded investigation into
the police action. The powerful National Religious Party even
threatened to topple the government if police take more actions
against the settlers.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Israel's Independence Day, Deputy Housing Minister
Meir Porush visited the hilltop settlement where he planted a
pomegranate tree in an apparent show of solidarity with the
settlers.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the rightitst political support, Yitzhar settlers
immediately rebuilt the demolished houses and set up more tents
and makeshift houses to reoccupy the hilltop.
</P>
<P>
The dispute on settlement expansion has been the leading
obstacle in reviving the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which
have been deadlocked since late March when Israel began building
the Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The PNA is demanding the halt to settlement expansion as a
precondition for resuming the peace negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
