<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mombasa Port Registers Increases by Eight Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's port of Mombasa registered
about eight percent growth in total cargo handling throughput
last year, reflecting improved regional economic performance.
</P>
<P>
The amount of cargo handled at the port increased from some
7,984,000 tons in 1995 to more than 8,694,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
The port's outgoing Executive Chairman, Robert Breneissen, was
quoted as saying that the cargo increase at the port was mainly
attributed to the transit traffic increasing by 37.5 percent in
1996.
</P>
<P>
He noted that transit traffic had become a major component of
the port's total throughput, rising from 1.9 million tons in 1995
to 2.8 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Uganda remains Mombasa's main external user whose cargo rose
from about 303,000 tons in 1991 to 1.2 million tons last year
while transit cargo of Tanzania through the port increased
dramatically from 91,000 tons in 1995 to 363,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the cargo handled at the port for Rwanda and Zaire
amounted to 474,000 tons and 143,000 tons respectively.
</P>
<P>
Containerized traffic also registered a significant growth
with 217,000 twenty-foot equivalent units (TEU) handled last year
as opposed to 200,000 TEUs in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
