<HEADLINE> Kenya-Mauritius Trade Volume Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Kenya and Mauritius
reached 13.43 million U.S. Dollars last year, up from 10.3
million Dollars in 1995, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are determined to keep the trade volume
rising since they started trade cooperation efforts in 1995, said
Kenyan Minister for Commerce and Industry Joshua Angatia here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya organized the first-ever trade exhibition and a trade
investment and tourism workshop in Mauritius in July 1995, then
Mauritius held two successful buyer and seller meetings in
Nairobi in September, 1995 and August, 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The response was good," Angatia said yesterday at the opening
of a buyer and seller meeting sponsored by Mauritius Freeport
Authority and attended by 25 Mauritian firms.
</P>
<P>
The firms deal in textiles, electronics, building materials,
pharmaceuticals, foodstuffs, paper, automotives and footwear.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius Freeport Authority's Deputy Director General
Rajakrishna Chellapermal said that his organization, founded in
1992 by the Mauritian government, aims to make the island country
a regional warehousing, distribution and marketing center.
</P>
<P>
Mauritian investors are exploring opportunities of setting up
export processing operations in Kenya, Zambia, Mozambique and
Malawi, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
