<HEADLINE> Grey-Headed Gulls Abundant in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- A large number of globally
threatened grey-headed gulls has been discovered on Musanbwa
island of Uganda in Lake Victoria, reported the local daily "the
New Vision" today.
</P>
<P>
The East African National History Society Uganda branch was
quoted as saying that Uganda has more gulls on the island than
the world's estimated total.
</P>
<P>
The branch stumbled on the birds while on a countrywide survey
to identify "important bird areas of Uganda."
</P>
<P>
According to an official of the branch, the island off Sango
Bay near Tanzania has more than 100,000 gulls, compared to about
100,000 worldwide, meaning Uganda has more grey-headed gulls than
the world population.
</P>
<P>
The water birds are slightly bigger than cattle egrets and
predominantly feed on fish, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said the biggest threat to the Musdambwa gulls is rampant
collection of eggs, along with those of little egrets which have
few known breeding sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Strives to Bring Down Trade Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam hopes to promote exports to
reduce the trade deficit when a series of regulations encouraging
exports come into effect in June, the Vietnam News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam will continue to import advanced equipment and
machinery to boost domestic production, although the increasing
trade deficit is causing worries, the Vietnam News quoted Trade
Minister Le Van Triet as saying.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that the trade deficit this year will be 4.3
billion U.S. dollars compared to nearly four billion dollars last
year. This means that the trade deficit per month will be 358
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, official statistics show that in the first three
months of this year, the trade deficit was only 900 million
dollars, much lower than expected, thanks to a series of measures
taken by the Trade Ministry, the Vietnam News reported.
</P>
<P>
The measures included the encouragement of any form of exports,
seeking new markets and limiting imports in the form of low
payments.
</P>
<P>
The ministry estimated that the trade deficit in the second
quarter will be 1.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Triet affirmed that imports of advanced technology and
machinery will increase from the present 33 percent to about 45
percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The trade ministry said all measures must be taken to limit the
imports of commonly used goods.
</P>
<P>
The Trade Ministry hopes that the measures to be introduced in
June will help Vietnam become one of the world's major exporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
