<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rescue Operation Ends in East Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The rescue operation has come to an
end in the quake-stricken east Iran except in four villages, the
state-run Tehran Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The operation to unearth the victims is continuing in the four
villages.
</P>
<P>
However, the radio and official news agency IRNA did not give
the latest death toll in the morning news program. The state
television reported 4,000 deaths Monday night.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Qaen Governor's office told Xinhua in a
telephone interview that they have buried 1,500 victims so far.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the rescue operation process is slow
because relief workers are using hands to search victims because
they can not use machines.
</P>
<P>
He said that the death toll reported by the media is just
estimation by some officials. The figure may be high or may be
low.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian headquarters in charge of natural disaster relief
work said that the rescue operation has been involved with six
helicopters, eight C-130 aircraft, 300 light and heavy
automobiles, 110 ambulances along with medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
So far more than 11,000 makeshift tents, 35,000 blankets and
100 tons of foodstuffs have been distributed among victims in
Qaen and Birjand regions.
</P>
<P>
The government called on the people to continue their support
to victims by donating plastic sheets, cooking stoves, lanterns,
portable power generators, shoes and clothing, blankets and
canned food.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 195 aftershocks have jolted the two
regions which were rocked by a powerful 7.1-degree earthquake on
Saturday noon.
</P>
<P>
The Geophysics Institute of Tehran University said that the
magnitudes of the aftershocks ranged from 3 to 5.5 degrees on the
Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
Although rescue operation has basically ended, inflow of
international assistance is pouring into Iran. France,
Switzerland, Pakistan and Kuwait have sent five planes carrying
foodstuffs and medicines for quake victims in Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Red Crescent Society of Turkey Monday sent 20 tons of
goods, comprising of sugar, medicines, blankets, cooking oil and
rice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
