<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Uses Foreign Funds in Afforestation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Yunnan, the "kingdom of plants" in
southwest China, has introduced World Bank loans and donated money
for the protection of forests and afforestation there.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Yunnan provincial government said that the
six Sino-foreign cooperative afforestation and forest protection
projects have brought the province a total of 400 million yuan
(nearly 50 million US dollars) of foreign and government
investment.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has rich varieties of tropical, subtropical plants, and
nearly all major varieties of world vegetation. The province
has established more than 100 nature reserves to protect its plant
resources.
</P>
<P>
Germany, the Netherlands, Japan, New Zealand, and the World Bank
have sent scientists and officials to make investigations in the
province.
</P>
<P>
With 170 million yuan (about 21 million dollars) of investment
from the World Bank and the Ministry of Forestry, 78,000 hectares
of commercial-timber forests have built in five counties.
</P>
<P>
The province also utilized 12 million deutsche marks donated by
Germany and 31 million yuan (3.8 million dollars) in supporting
funds from the Chinese government to build 26,000 hectares of
forests in another six counties where vegetation had been
seriously damaged.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the 15 million dollars offered by the Dutch
government was used to establish organizations for protecting
tropical rain forests in Simao, Gaoligong Mountain, Tongbiguan,
and some other areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
