<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lee Kuan Yew: Patten Breaches What London Agreed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew of
Singapore said that Hong Kong Governor Chris Patten breached what
the British agreed to in handling the Hong Kong affairs and that
incoming chief executive Tung Chee Hwa should scrap all of
Patten's reforms.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspapers today, in an interview with the
Financial Times of London, which was published Monday, Lee said,
"If I were Tung, I would adopt laws and regulations in Hong Kong
as they were pre-Patten." "Anything post-Pattern I would leave
out. It can be done simply by an omnibus clause," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Senior Minister said that he told Patten before he took
office as governor that all would be well if he kept within the
spirit and the letter of the Joint Declaration and the Basic Law.
"But he did not."
</P>
<P>
In reproducing the Financial Times article, the Straits Times
noted, "Interestingly, the FT article omitted parts of the
interview in which Mr. Lee spoke about how Governor Patten had
ignored his advice to keep within the letter and spirit of the
Joint Declaration and the Basic Law."
</P>
<P>
The paper then reproduced the part of the interview omitted by
the Financial Times, which asked Lee, "So he's (Chris Patten)
handled it wrongly?"
</P>
<P>
Lee replied, "Patten has indeed. I gave him my view that as
long as he kept within the letter and spirit of the Joint
Declaration and the Basic Law, all would be well. But he did not
... Ask Percy Craddock. He's written several articles on this.
Percy's a contemporary of mine at Cambridge. He did something most
unusual for a Foreign Office man, and so did David Wilson and
Murray Maclehose."
</P>
<P>
"Three Foreign Service officers, who reached high up the apex,
came out publicly to say that Patten was breaching what the
British agreed to. ...What better evidence? These were the British
representatives the Chinese negotiated with," he continued.
</P>
<P>
"My guess is people in Hong Kong are a pragmatic lot. They know
that they have to live with the PRC. Once that red flag with the
five yellow stars goes up and the PLA -- 10,000 of them, deployed
on ceremonial occasions -- everyone will understand that things
are different. It's no longer Chris Patten pressing flesh," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"If that is derailed then the whole of East Asia is in trouble.
We are probably not in as much trouble as Taiwan or Hong Kong who
are most dependent on China trade and investments. But every
country in Asia is investing in China," the Senior Minister noted.
</P>
<P>
"If you decide to put the screws on China, you'll be alone in
Asia, because the countries of Asia have got to live with this
gigantic mammoth," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the Financial Times article, Lee was quoted as saying that
Patten's democratic reforms and his Bill of Rights went beyond
what had been agreed with Britain in the Sino-British Joint
Declaration of 1984 and the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
"He (Mr. Tung) has to do all the unpleasant things early and
give people a clear understanding of the basis on which he will
govern," Lee said, adding, "But on political security issues, if
he does not manage Hong Kong in a way that protects China's
interests, I see a very difficult time for him and Hong Kong," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
