<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ROUNDUP: Sri Lanka's Economic Performance in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- In 1996, Sri Lanka's economic
growth slowed down to 3.8 percent from 5.5 percent in 1995 due to
a severe drought and rising spending on the ethnic war.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Sri Lanka's real GDP increased 3.8 percent as
agricultural and industrial activities recovered steadily from the
depressed conditions experienced in the first part of the year due
to drought and power cuts, said the Central Bank in its annual
report for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Despite this weakness, the country's open trade and payments
policy regime helped minimize output losses and prevented a
sharper increase in prices, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The GDP at market prices increased 15.1 percent to reach 13,932
million U.S. dollars. With a mid-year population of 18.315
million, this indicated a per capita nominal income level of 760
dollars in 1996. When adjusted for net foreign factor income, the
per capita national product would be 753 dollars, the report
noted.
</P>
<P>
The Gross National Product (GNP) increased 3.1 percent in real
terms in 1996. When adjusted for population growth of 1.1 percent,
the per capita real GNP increased 2 percent in 1996, compared with
the 4.5 percent the previous year.
</P>
<P>
After slowing down in the first half of the year, exports and
imports picked up during the second half. For the year as a whole
exports grew 13 percent and imports 7 percent, resulting in a
reduction of the trade deficit to 9.4 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
This was largely due to an improvement in tea prices as real
exports grew only 4 percent
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit of the balance of payments
declined  one percentage point to 3.9 percent of GDP in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Towards the latter part of the year, private foreign investment
recovered significantly, though relatively small compared to past
inflows.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the higher domestic inflation and the weakening
balance of payments, the Sri Lanka rupee depreciated by about 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
In terms of per capita income, Sri Lanka has reached the
threshold of becoming a middle income developing country in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices as indicated by the Colombo Consumer Price
Index increased 15.9 percent, whereas the overall price level, as
indicated by GDP inflator, showed an increase of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the liquidity over-hang from 1995, monetary
expansion remained high owing to continued high credit growth to
both government and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector suffered most from the drought with the
real value added declining 4.6 percent in 1996 in contrast to an
annual growth rate of 2.4 percent during the 1991 to 1995 period.
</P>
<P>
The drought affected mainly the non-plantation agricultural
output and coconut in the plantation sector. The paddy sector
which was hard hit by the drought registered a 27 percent drop in
output while prices increased 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tea production after a record output the previous year rose
further 5 percent and tea prices increased 44 percent to reach
record levels.
</P>
<P>
Rubber production recorded a 6 percent increase and prices too
remained attractive. Coconut production declined 7.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Value added in mining and quarrying rose 8.9 percent compared
with 3.4 percent the previous year. Gem exports increased 16
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
