<HEADLINE> Nepal Permits Power Export from Hydro Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
permitted an Australian company to export electricity from a major
hydro power project in west Nepal, which is to become the
country's first export-oriented project to be built entirely with
foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on the project's export authorization was signed
last week between the government and Australia's Snowy Mountain
Engineering Corp., which is now registered as West Seti Hydro
Electricity Corp., sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the authorization documents enables the West
Seti Project's Australian promoter to start negotiations with
potential electricity buyers in neighboring India, they said.
</P>
<P>
The 750-megawatt West Seti Project, with an estimated cost of 1
billion U.S. dollars, is located about 400 km west of Kathmandu
and not far from Nepal's western border with India.
</P>
<P>
The Australian company has a plan to export all the electricity
generated by the project to several State Electricity Boards of
India's northern region, which will face a power supply shortage
of 21,000 megawatts by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the project is expected to start next year and
be completed in six years if agreements on the project's
development and operation could be reached between the government
and the Australian developer, Nepali officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
