<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Coal Production to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's coal production will
increase to 86 million tons in 2000 from 54 million tons in 1996,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
President director of Bukit Asam Coal Company R. A. Sunardi
said here Monday that at the end of the Seventh Five-Year
Development Plan in 2004, the country's coal output will continue
to increase to 109 million tons and to 139 million tons in 2009.
</P>
<P>
Coal mining business in Indonesia was started since the Dutch
colonial period. Up to the 1970s, Indonesia produced less than
500,000 tons of coal per annum. Coal mining increased with the oil
crisis in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Sunardi said in 1976, the government decided that coal was an
alternate energy of oil. Afterwards, coal mining in Indonesia
developed speedy and its coal production increased sharply from 2
million tons in 1985 to 54 million tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's potential coal reserve is estimated at 38 billion
tons, mostly in Sumatra, Kalimantan, Java, Irian Jaya and
Sulawesi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
