<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Giant Power Plant Operational in 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's giant Bakun
Hydroelectric Power Plant will go into commercial operation in
August 2003.
</P>
<P>
The Bakun Hydro-Electric Corporation (BHEC) Berhad (limited)
and a consortium of underwriters today signed here an
underwriting agreement for the construction of the 13.6 billion
ringgit (about 5.44 billion U.S. dollars) hydroelectric power
plant in Sarawak, east Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The signing was witnessed by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad who launched the corporate logo of BHEC on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Work on the project started last October and the plant is
scheduled to go into initial operation not later than October 31,
2002 and into commercial operation not later than August 31, 2003.
</P>
<P>
The power plant will have an installed capacity of 2,520
megawatts in Sarawak with power transmission system comprising
about 670 kilometer lines in the state and about 670 kilometer
submarine cables linked to Tenaga Nasional Bhd (TNB) (National
Power Limited)'s transmission system in Peninsular Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Ting's Ekran Berhad will hold 32 percent equity in BHEC, making
it the single largest shareholder, while the Sarawak state
government will hold 19 percent, Sarawak Electricity Supply
Corporation nine percent and TNB, the Malaysian government and the
Employees' Provident Fund will hold a five percent stake each.
</P>
<P>
Of the balance of 25 percent, 15 percent is allocated to the
Malaysian public and 10 percent to Malaysian and foreign
institutions.
</P>
<P>
BHEC will be listed on the main board of the Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange soon and is making a public issue of 375,000,000 new
ordinary shares of one ringgit (about 40 U.S. cents) at an issue
price of two ringgit (about 80 U.S. cents) per share.  
</P>
</TEXT>
