<HEADLINE> Approval Rate of New Zealand Government Drops: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The approval rate of the New
Zealand government has dropped further by 4 percent to only 14
percent six months after the formation of the new coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the disapproval rate climbed to 75 percent, shows
the latest poll.
</P>
<P>
The poll of 1,000 people, conducted by Colmar Brunton-One
Network News, found that in the coalition, the National Party now
enjoys a popularity rate of 38 percent, while its junior partner,
NZ First, has a support rate of only 4 percent compared with the
17 percent it scored on the election night.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, support for opposition Labor Party rose to
42 percent, topping the National for the first time since 1993.
</P>
<P>
However, observers said that Labor's rise is mainly the result
of the poor performance of the government.
</P>
<P>
The poll also found that broken election promises, a lack of
integrity among some ruling MPs, and disunity between the
coalition parties, are the most common reasons for the decline of
the government's popularity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
