<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clash Kills 2 in West Nepal Before Local Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Two men were killed in a fatal
clash between ruling party workers and a group of ultra-leftist
guerrillas in a western Nepali village, official daily the Rising
Nepal said today.
</P>
<P>
The clash took place Sunday in the village in Rolpa district,
about 250 kilometers west of Kathmandu, when some 30 guerrillas
made a sudden attack on the workers of Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand's National Democratic Party (RPP), who were meeting
at a teashop in connection with the coming local elections on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
One RPP worker and one member of the underground leftist
movement were killed in the clash with other four people seriously
injured, the paper quoted a district officer as saying.
</P>
<P>
As the local elections in west Nepal approaches near, the
underground leftist movement called "People's War", which earlier
called an election boycott, is reportedly beefing up its
anti-election activities including spreading death threats among
would-be candidates and carrying out bomb explosions to scare away
voters.
</P>
<P>
The underground guerrillas last week have killed three election
candidates, all from main opposition the Nepal Congress (NC)
party, in the same area.
</P>
<P>
Voters in west Nepal will elect their local administration
officers on Saturday in the first phase of the local elections,
while the polls in central and east Nepal will be held on May 26.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
