<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Ruling Parties Vow to Push Through Key Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Germany's two ruling
parties today vowed to brush aside the rejection from the main
opposition Social Democratic Party (SDP) and push through the
government plans to overhaul the country's tax and pension systems.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached here between Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and its Bavarian sister party
Christian Social Union (CSU) after the SDP decided earlier today
that it would not bargain with the government on pension reform.
</P>
<P>
The tax and pension reforms are among the key initiatives
proposed by the Bonn government to tackle the country's worsening
social problems, such as record high unemployment and a financial
crisis to support Germany's generous pension system.
</P>
<P>
The government and the opposition held three rounds of
negotiations on tax reform from February to April, when the talks
collapsed after both sides refused to give ground to each other.
</P>
<P>
Under its tax reform package, the government proposes to cut
Germany's top income tax rate of 53 percent to 39 percent, and
business taxes from 45 percent to 35 percent, so as to bolster
business confidence, investment and employment.
</P>
<P>
The SDP, however, has spoken in favor of keeping the top rate
intact or trimming it only modestly, a strategy meant to keep the
tax burden on the rich.
</P>
<P>
Under the pension reform proposal, the government hopes to cut
the pension of an average earner from present 70 percent of net
income to 64 percent. The SDP rejects cuts in retirement benefits,
arguing that the taxpayer should bear the burden of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
Oskar Lafontaine, the SDP's leader, announced today that his
party would weigh the pension reform through normal legislative
procedures rather than special negotiations with the government.
</P>
<P>
The government needs the SDP's support to pass any major reform
plan through the SDP-controlled upper house of parliament. Without
the SDP's prior approval, government initiatives will have to wend
their way through parliamentary committees, raising fears that
politicians and interest groups will water down the plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clearance of Unexploded Bombs in Laos Makes Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Clearance of unexploded ordnance
(UXO) in Laos has made slow but sure progress, with work in three
provinces having been completed, according to a report from
Vientiane.
</P>
<P>
Bombs dropped on Laos between 1964 and 1973 have been reported
in 15 of the country's 17 provinces.
</P>
<P>
The unexploded bombs are killing or wounding about 200 people a
year, according to the United Nations Development Program Office
in Vientiane.
</P>
<P>
Many baseball-sized bombs are accidentally detonated by farmers
at work or children at play, causing tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Since 1973, 11,500 people have been injured, with half of them
fatally.
</P>
<P>
UXO Laos, which handles bomb clearing activities with
assistance from the UNDP, said in a report that incidents are not
expected to decrease until a major clearance effort is launched.
</P>
<P>
UXO Laos plans to complete work in two more provinces this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
