<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Strives to be Among the First for EMU Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Italy will try its best to be in the
first group to join the single European currency, Italian Prime
Minister Romano Prodi said to the French daily La Tribune today.
</P>
<P>
"Italy is determined to use all its political instruments at
its disposal" to ensure the lira joins the single currency, the
Euro, as planned in 1999, Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said the current task for his country is to make its
European Union (EU) partners believe that the financial situation
here is stable.
</P>
<P>
The lira dropped out of the Exchange Rate Mechanism (ERM) in a
currency crisis in 1992 and did not return to it until four years
later in November 1996. Since then it has devalued considerably.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said Italy is now launching structural spending reforms
to further cut public deficit in a bid to meet the strict 3
percent level of deficit in the gross domestic product regulated
by the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
However, Rome's efforts failed to win the nods from its EU
partners. EU finance ministers meeting in Brussels today approved
a report on the state of Italy's finances, saying many of the
country's measures taken to cut budget deficit were not
sustainable.
</P>
<P>
When asked about Spain's and Portugal's membership of the
single currency, Prodi said it was important that the two
countries be included in the European Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
After all, an Europe without the contribution of Latin culture
was impossible to exist, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
