<HEADLINE> Annan to Put Forth U.N. Reform Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan will raise in June and July an overall plan for U.N.
financial and political reforms, Japanese newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived here Sunday on a four-day visit, talked with
Japanese Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda on Monday evening and
said the reform of the world body has reached a "crucial stage."
</P>
<P>
Ikeda urged the U.N. chief to carry out financial and political
reforms in a "well balanced" way, saying the Japanese public will
not accept boosting its contribution to the U.N. budget without
progress in reforming the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Meeting earlier in the day with Juro Saito, president of
Japan's House of Councillors, or the upper house of parliament,
Annan said there was a possibility that five more permanent seats
would be created for the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"Japan stands a good chance" of winning one of the seats, he
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Annan also met Japan's House of Representatives Speaker
Soichiro Ito, Defense Agency Chief Fumio Kyuma and visited Emperor
Akihito and Empress Michiko earlier in the day. 
</P>
