<HEADLINE> Clinton Returns to Face Domestic Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
returned home from the Caribbean on Monday to confront the pile of
work, not the least the row with Congress over a juvenile crime
bill.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives passed the bill last week,
dropping a good part of Clinton's original plan, including more
funds for gang prosecutions, banning gun sales to 18-year-olds
with juvenile criminal record and requiring gun dealers to add
child safety locks to weapons.
</P>
<P>
Aides to the president said he has to negotiate with the
lawmakers to reclaim the huge portions, the Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is also scheduled to issue an apology on Friday to
eight elderly survivors of a federal study in Tuskegee, Alabama,
that monitored the effects of untreated syphilis in black men.
</P>
<P>
The experiment has been going on for 40 years without the men's
knowledge, well after penicillin became the standard treatment in
1947 for the sexually transmitted disease.
</P>
<P>
The apology precedes a major address on race by Clinton on June
14 in San Diego, one of three commencement addresses the president
will deliver over the next six weeks.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will also resume his push for national testing
standards in schools, which he described as part of his 21st
century agenda. The Congress opposes the idea and is seeking to
trim 760 federal education programs.
</P>
<P>
Aides said Clinton will stick to his standards proposal,
linking it to education proposals under the balanced budget
agreement he has struck with Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
