<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Re-attaches Vital Importance to Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The recently concluded Latin
American tour by United States President Bill Clinton -- delayed
as it was -- has demonstrated the region's importance to the
world's only superpower.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's tour through Latin America was the first since he
took office in January 1993. From May 5 to 12, he visited Mexico,
Costa Rica and the Barbados to attend a summit with Central
American and Caribbean heads of state in San Jose and in
Bridgetown, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is planning to make his second tour through the region
this October when he will visit Venezuela, Brazil and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the Cold War, the world has been advancing
rapidly towards multipolarization. The unification of Europe and
the surge ahead of Asia have brought new challenges to the U.S.
in the international arena.
</P>
<P>
Engrossed in relations with Europe and the Asia-Pacific region
since he took up residence in the White House, Clinton had delayed
visiting Latin America, arousing a sense of indifference to the
region.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the European Union (EU) and Asia have been
turning to the huge Latin American market of nearly 500 million
potential consumers. Visits by Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto and European Union bloc leaders were among them.
</P>
<P>
What is worth mentioning is French President Jacques Chirac's
March visit to Latin America, a gesture to free the region from
U.S. control and seek economic cooperation with the EU in the area.
</P>
<P>
Within this context, Clinton made his Latin American trip to
show the extreme importance that Washington attaches to the
region's strategic position.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the U.S has unilaterally "certified" a
drug war against Latin American countries, intervening in their
internal affairs and hurting their national dignity.
</P>
<P>
When a new immigration law came into effect in the United
States last April, countries in the region were worried about
possible damage done to their economies by mass deportations of
Latin American immigrants living in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, frictions and trade disputes frequently occur
between the U.S. and countries of this region. Bilateral ties are
still tense, with Latin American nations who demand that Washington
develop relationships with the region which respect their
sovereignty and cooperate on an equal footing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jakarta Bans "Mega-Bintang" Banners in Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government banned
Monday banners and pictures of 'Mega-Bintang' which suggest an
alliance between deposed Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) leader
Megawati Soekarnoputri and the United Development Party (PPP)
during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Mega is Megawati's nickname and Bintang or star is the PPP's
symbol.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the General Election Committee Moch Yogie S.M. said
here last night that banners and slogans breached election rules
and an agreement among the three political parties contesting the
May 29 poll.
</P>
<P>
The three parties -- the ruling party Golkar, the PPP and the
PDI started their campaign on April 27. The campaign will run till
May 23.
</P>
<P>
"I declare that people are not to use those banners. We never
recognize any party but the three poll contestants," Yogie said.
</P>
<P>
Banners and yells in support of Megawati have become the
highlight of many PPP rallies since the party's branch chief
Mudrick Setiawan Sangidoe in Surakarta, central Java, met Megawati
last week to seek her blessing for many of her local loyalists who
wanted to join the PPP.
</P>
<P>
Megawati is not allowed to stand for election. But she insists
that she is the legitimate PDI chairwoman despite a
government-backed congress held in June last year that reinstated
Soerjadi at the party's helm.
</P>
<P>
The Soerjadi-led PDI faction, the PPP and the Golkar will vie
for 425 seats in the 500-seat House of Representatives in the
forthcoming election. The other 75 seats are reserved for the
military, whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Attorney General Singgih also confirmed the ban. He
said election rules said that campaign banners should carry the
party's programs or themes and must be approved by police.
</P>
<P>
Armed forces chief of sociopolitical affairs Lt. Gen. Syarwan
Hamid also said the security forces would seize banners or
T-shirts and ban chants in support of the 'Mega-Bintang' alliance.
</P>
<P>
Yogie also urged the parties again to stop their illegal street
rallies.
</P>
<P>
"The street rallies are on the increase despite the ban, not
because we tolerate them doing so but because we lack the security
guards to stop them," Yogie said.
</P>
<P>
Street rallies have claimed at least 39 lives since campaigning
began on April 27, official sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Attaches Vital Importance to L.American Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For its part, the U.S. needs to put away the disputes and be on
good terms in order to make its strategic global objective a
reality.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Mexico, Clinton talked with his Mexican
counterpart, Ernesto Zedillo, and they signed 11 agreements of
cooperation and issued two declarations on anti-drug
alliances and the settlement of immigration
problems. The two sides, to a certain extent, reached
understandings.
</P>
<P>
In San Jose, the U.S. president met with the presidents of
Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, Nicaragua and the
Dominican Republic as well as the prime minister of Belize,
and issued the "Declaration of San Jose" at the end of this summit.
</P>
<P>
The document underscores the need to strengthen the
relationship of "friends and partners" between the United States
and the above-mentioned countries, and stipulates concrete
commitments.
</P>
<P>
At the summit in Bridgetown, Barbados, Clinton told heads of 14
member nations of the Caribbean Community, or CARICOM, that his
country will not forget the Caribbean nations in the American
integration process. They identified mutual interests of trade,
anti-drug operations and immigration.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's tour has further defined "an agenda for the American
continent vis-a-vis the upcoming century," his spokesman said.
Vital relations between the U.S. and Latin America were
re-established.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, from Latin American observers' view, both sides
differed a lot in their positions, and there were many
contradictions on issues that had to do with the sovereignty of
states and national dignity of Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
In their opinion, relations between the U.S. and
Latin America will head down a windy path if Washington does not
radically change the gunboat diplomacy it employs in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
