<HEADLINE> Laos Demands Halt to Sand Dredging in Border River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Laos has protested against sand
dredging along the Mekong river by Thai companies, saying that the
operations are affecting deep-water channels which serve as border
lines between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a note of protest sent earlier this year, the Laotian side
urged the Thai government "to impose stricter enforcement of
regulations on the dredging companies, which have shown concern
only for their own interests and never for any regulation or
bilateral ties," according to a Thai Government House source.
</P>
<P>
There are about 90 sand dredging operations in five Thai
provinces along the Mekong river, of which 75 are in the
northeastern provinces of Nong Khai and Nakhon Phanom, where the
greatest impact to the deep-water channels are reported.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Government House source said the dredging was causing
redirecting of the channels into the Thai territory and was
damaging to the river's banks.
</P>
<P>
As a result the Thai authorities have long been forced to spend
money rebuilding embankments, the source said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Foreign Ministry has asked the Interior Ministry to
order dredging halt, but the Interior Ministry prefers to see the
problem solved locally by provincial authorities of both
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
