<HEADLINE> World Bank to Boost Credits to Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has agreed to
provide a new credit package of 625 million U.S. dollars to
Romania, the bank's president James Wolfensohn said today.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn, here for a three-day stay on the first visit by a
World Bank president in 20 years, told a news conference that
disbursement of 330 million dollars would occur this year.
</P>
<P>
The credit package was "a real sign of our confidence in the
country," he said, adding that the Washington-based World Bank had
been backing Romania's measures to restructure its economy.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank credits included 350 million dollars for
reforming the farm sector, 50 million dollars to underpin social
benefits and cushion the effect of rapid change, 150 million
dollars to upgrade roads, 50 million dollars for higher education
and 25 million dollars to improve water supplies.
</P>
<P>
Together with the new package, a further 80 million dollars was
likely to be approved within a week under a resumed disbursement
of an earlier loan for restructuring the country's enterprises.
</P>
<P>
All the credits have yet to be approved by the board of
directors of the bank.
</P>
<P>
Since arriving here on Sunday, Wolfensohn has met Romanian
President Emil Constantinescu and Prime Minister Victor Ciorbea
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the International Monetary Fund approved 430
million dollars credits to Romania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
