<HEADLINE> Jakarta Not Worry About Being on U.S. Priority Watch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia should not worry about
being put on the United States' priority watch list, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
"Inclusion in the list is something common and should not be
feared," Coordinating Minister for Production and Distribution
Hartarto said here on Monday afternoon after a general election
campaign rally, the official Antara news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto however did not elaborate why Indonesia does not worry
about the status.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Indonesia could do something about the listing
through lobbying, the minister said, "that is up to Tunky
(industry and trade minister)".
</P>
<P>
Tunky Ariwibowo held talks with a U.S. trade representative in
Montreal, Canada, on May 8, 1997, mainly about Indonesia's
national car policy but they also talked about the priority watch
list and GSP (generalized system of preferences).
</P>
<P>
GSP is a U.S. trade facility affecting imports from developing
countries including Indonesia. For Indonesia the facility will
expire in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
Tunky implored the U.S. not to include Indonesia again in the
priority watch list, arguing that the Indonesian government had
improved its system to protect intellectual property rights.
</P>
