<HEADLINE> Japan Fires Ambassador to Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The move came after the ministry, on the same day, received a
resignation from the ambassador, in acceptance of some
responsibility for the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We have heard yet again Ambassador Morihisa Aoki's desire to
step down and after considering many things, we have decided to
ask him to leave the post," Ikeda told a special parliamentary
session.
</P>
<P>
On December 17 last year, rebels from the Tupac Amaru
Revolution Movement in Peru seized the ambassador's residence
during a party celebrating the Japan's emperor's birthday. The
rebels held 72 people for more than four months.
</P>
<P>
The crisis ended last month when Peruvian troops stormed the
residence, rescuing all but one hostage alive and killing all 14
rebels.
</P>
<P>
Morihisa Aoki has been under criticism for the failure of
security measures at the party, and his behavior during and after
the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
