<HEADLINE> Traffic Control System Found Effective at East Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Traffic across the Pusan metropolitan
area was reduced by about 15 percent since "a passenger car odds-evens
number ban system" was introduced, police sources said here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The system resulted in a 30-minute decrease in driving time from
the athletes' village at Haeundae Beach to Kudok Stadium, the venue
for the grand ceremonies and the track and field events, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Citizens are only allowed to drive their private passenger cars
every other day during the Pusan East Asian Games. Cars with
even-numbered license plates are permitted to drive on even-numbered
days, and those with odd plates on odd days.
</P>
<P>
The system will remain in effect until May 19, covering the hours
of 7 o'clock in the morning to 9 o'clock in the night.
</P>
<P>
There are over 430,000 privately-owned cars in the city,
representing about half of the automobiles on the roads, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
If the license plate system is carried out successfully, it should
cause a daily 25 percent traffic reduction, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, only a 10 to 15 percent practical reduction is expected
during the Games, due to an influx of cars from around South Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for More Public Service Advertisements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- China has required manufacturers
and businesses that do frequent advertising through Chinese
television, radio and newspapers this year to produce at least one
public-service advertisement for media.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration for Industry and Commerce (SAIC) said
Monday that those public-service ads are required to be issued for
TV, radio and newspapers at or above provincial level.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily reported that advertising agencies with
leading positions in each province, autonomous region and
municipality are also asked to produce a public service
advertisement for media.
</P>
<P>
A SAIC official said that "these public-service ads will mainly
by issued by TV, radio, newspaper and pubic places in September,
a month designated by SAIC last year to help enchance social
progress and health development of the advertising industry in
China."
</P>
<P>
The official said that media agencies should issue at least one
public-service advertisement during prime-time hours, from 6 pm to
9 pm, or on major pages of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The theme for this year's activity will focus on promotion the
spirit of the Chinese nation and its unremitting efforts to become
stronger.
</P>
<P>
Last year's month-long promotion of public-service ads -- which
focused on "traditional virtues of the Chinese nation" such as
thrift, respect for the elderly and care for children -- succeeded
in refining professional ethic on the part of people who produce
and issue advertisements.
</P>
<P>
Some 16,860 public-service ads were issued last September.
</P>
</TEXT>
