<HEADLINE> Austria to Take Time Considering Whether to Join NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Austria will decide on its own when
to consider joining the enlarged NATO and the European security
mechanism, Austrian Federal Chancellor Viktor Klima said today.
</P>
<P>
Klima, who also chairs the Social Democratic Party, said there
should not be a false impression that Austria must decide whether
to join the Western military alliance in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
"We still have enough time to observe and analyze on the
development of the European security mechanism and then make a
decision," he told a foreign policy session of his party.
</P>
<P>
Noting that entering a new bloc is not in the foreign policy of
the ruling Social Democratic Party, Klima reiterated that such a
decision must be made through a national referendum.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the European Monetary Union (EMU) will
be kicked off on January 1, 1999, as scheduled, and that the EMU's
delay or failure will result in serious economic setbacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
