<HEADLINE> Dalian Free Trade Zone Opens Wider to Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Dalian Mayor Bo Xilai is urging
foreign investors not to ignore the huge market in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
There is a huge market in northeast China and along the
Bohai Bay, today's "China Daily" quoted Bo as saying.
</P>
<P>
As the most open city in this region, Dalian will actively turn
the Free Trade Zone into a key area for consolidating co-operation
with foreign investors this year, Bo said at a symposium on the
investment environment of the Dalian Free Trade Zone held in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Started in 1992, the zone has developed into a special economic
area with commerce, processing, industry and storage as its
pillars.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, an accumulated 1,200 projects had been
founded in the zone, with contractual investments of 1.35 billion
US dollars. Of them, almost half are foreign-funded projects,
binding pledged foreign capital of 450 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Businesses from 25 nations and regions so far have established
offices in the zone.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Lihua, director of the Administrative Committee of the
Free Trade Zone, said foreign investors enjoy preferences in the
zone ranging from tax-exemption for capital goods imports to a
free settlement system for foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
Dalian expects to build the zone into an export processing base
and an import and export commodities distribution center in the
northeast Asian region within five years, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
