<HEADLINE> Loan Agreement Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Standard Charted Bank of the
United Kingdom has offered five million US dollars in working
capital loans to China Golden Valley International Trust and
Investment Corp, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, signed yesterday in Beijing, the Standard
Charted Bank will grant the loans with an interest rate that is
only 0.3 percent higher over the London Interbank Offered Rate.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper quotes Ni Ying, a staff of the
International Business Department of Golden Valley as saying that
the money is expected to be used to support the import and export
business of the firm's customers in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Chunlong, marketing manager of the Standard Chartered
Bank's operations in North China, said it is unusual for the bank
to lend loans of such a large amount to financial firms.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Standard Charted Bank has set up seven branch banks
and eight representative offices in China, topping all
overseas-invested banks in this regard.
</P>
<P>
It has been approved to open local currency services in the
Shanghai Pudong New Area, and the operation is expected to begin
in June, the paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM to Urge Yangon to Certify Illegal Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh will urge Yangon to certify the citizenship of
Myanmar working illegally in Thailand, a step that will facilitate
the legalization of their working status in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was discussed Monday during a meeting between
government officials and the National Security Council (NSC),
chaired by Chavalit Yongchaiyudh.
</P>
<P>
It will be among the key topics of discussion with Myanmar's
leaders, when Chavalit visits Myanmar this Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We do our part in registering them and give them two years to
work in Thailand. But once the registration takes place, Myanmar
will have to certify their citizenship so as to make the
legalization of their working (here) become effective," NSC chief
Bunsak was quoted today by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
A temporary measure giving two-year concessionary work permit
to illegal foreign workers from the neighboring countries of
Myanmar, Laos and Cambodia allowing them to work in Thailand's 43
provinces has failed to meet its objectives to control their
movement.
</P>
<P>
During his forthcoming visit, Chavalit will also urge his
Myanmar counterpart to move towards introducing convertible
currency to remove foreign exchange risks for Thai traders.
</P>
<P>
Thai traders have complained about the foreign exchange risk
because they have to deal with double currency exchange rates: an
official rate of six kyat, and the more realistic rate of 170 kyat
per dollar, according to Virachai Techavichit, an adviser to the
prime minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
