<HEADLINE> 2 Parties to Merge for 1998 Philippine Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Two opposition parties, one of them
the biggest one in the Philippines, have moved a step closer to
merge for the 1998 presidential elections by agreeing to speak in
one voice on vital issues.
</P>
<P>
The Laban Ng Demokratikong Pilipino (Laban), the largest
opposition party, and the Nationalist People's Coalition reached
agreement amidst renewed attempts by the Presidential Palace to
restore the alliance between Laban and the ruling Lakas-NUCD
party, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The two parties would have a common stand on concerns that
would affect the country's political and economic stability,
particularly the administration-backed efforts to lift or extend
the term limit for President Fidel Ramos by amending the
Constitution, Laban Chairman Edgardo Angara said.
</P>
<P>
Angara said the two parties had formed a joint committee to
oversee their common advocacy agenda which would focus on good
government.
</P>
<P>
They also sealed a covenant for clean elections, and for
electoral reforms to protect the Filipinos' will in next year's
polls, Angara added.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines will hold its national elections in June next
year.  
</P>
