<HEADLINE> HK PLC Invites Public Opinions Over Two Draft Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Secretariat of the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) Monday invited members of the public
and interested groups to voice their views on the National Flag
and National Emblem Bill and the Regional Flag and Regional Emblem
Bill.
</P>
<P>
The two draft bills were tabled to the May 3 meeting of the PLC
for first and second readings, and then debate was adjoined and a
Bills Committee, chaired by legislator Ho Sai-chu, was formed to
study the bills.
</P>
<P>
The National Flag and National Emblem Bill seeks to adopt, by
means of local legislation, relevant provisions of the 1990 Law on
the National Flag of China and the 1991 Law on the National Emblem
of China in the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Provisions prohibiting disrespectful acts to the national flag
and national emblem and restricting the occasions on which the
national flag and the national emblem may be displayed are
included in the bill.
</P>
<P>
The Regional Flag and Regional Emblem Bill adopts the
provisions in the Provisional arrangements on the Use of the
Regional Flag and the Regional Emblem of the HKSAR endorsed by the
Preparatory Committee for the HKSAR in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release by the Secretariat located in
Shenzhen, interested people and groups can meet members of the
Bill Committee to voice their views, send their written
submissions by mail or to the Secretariat homepage on the
Internet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970513.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (79-80) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (79-80) in a
question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: How will government-involved contracts straddling
1997 become valid after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Contracts in Hong Kong can be divided into two main
categories.
</P>
<P>
1) Ordinary commercial contracts, civil contracts and ordinary
land leases approved before 1997.
</P>
<P>
2) Contracts that straddle 1997 and involve the
responsibilities, rights, interests and obligations of the Hong
Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
The first category of contracts will be recognized after 1997
as long as they do not contravene the Basic Law, whereas the
second category of contracts will not be valid unless an agreement
is reached on their validity after consultations between the
Chinese and British sides.
</P>
<P>
For example, Annex 2 of the Sino-British Joint Declaration says
that one of the functions of the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group
is "to discuss matters relating to the smooth transfer of
government in 1997," that, in the latter half of the transitional
period, "there will be need for closer cooperation" between the
Chinese and British governments, and that "matters for
consideration" during this period "shall include procedures to be
adopted for the smooth transition in 1997."
</P>
<P>
In the Memorandum of Understanding Concerning the Construction
of the New Airport in Hong Kong and Related Questions, the Chinese
and British governments agreed that, on important matters relating
to projects of the airport that straddle June 30, 1997, the two
governments will engage in consultations in the spirit of
cooperation and in accordance with the Joint Declaration.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum specifically states that the British side will
consult the Chinese side through the Airport Committee before the
British Hong Kong government grants major airport-related
franchises or contracts, or guarantees for airport-related debt,
that extend beyond June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
With regard to government-involved contracts resulting from
previous laws that contravene the Basic Law, loan contracts signed
by the British Hong Kong government without approval of the
Sino-British Joint Liaison Group, or franchises that have been
unilaterally granted by the British Hong Kong government and that
will harm the interests of the Hong Kong SAR, they will be either
revised or canceled after 1997 in accordance with procedures as
stipulated in the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Question: Will social organizations and individuals be
permitted to establish schools?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Schools operated by social organizations and
individuals are an important part of Hong Kong's educational
system and have played an irreplaceable role in the development of
educational undertakings there.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, the educational system and its
operational methods will remain unchanged after 1997, and
community organizations and individuals may, in accordance with
law, operate various types of educational undertakings in the Hong
Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
This will be highly beneficial to the development of education
in the Hong Kong SAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
