<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador, Peru Negotiate Border Disputes in Brasilia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- An Ecuadoran negotiating team left
for Brasilia today for the second round of talks with Peru to
settle territorial disputes between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations will begin Wednesday and will continue until
May 21, as agreed on by the two parties in the first round of
talks in Brasilia last month, said Ecuadoran Foreign Ministry
officials.
</P>
<P>
In this round of talks, negotiators will tackle two more
controversial points: Lagartococha and the Zarumilla Canal.
</P>
<P>
The 11-member Ecuadoran team, which is led by Edgar Teran
Teran, has two support groups: one from the Foreign Ministry and
the other from the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
A support group of the guarantor countries of the Rio de
Janeiro Protocol -- Argentina, Brazil, Chile and the United States
-- will also take part in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Border disputes between Ecuador and Peru can be traced back to
the early 1940s.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed the Rio Protocol in 1942 to agree on a
cease-fire and a border demarcation.
</P>
<P>
But the two countries were engaged in a brief war at the
beginning of 1995 and have tried to negotiate a final settlement
since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
