<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austalian Woman Finishes Swim from Havana to Key West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Just 24 hours after leaving
Havana, Australian woman Susie Maroney completed a 180 kilometers
crossing swim between Cuba and the Florida Keys on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Maroney came ashore on the small sandy beach at Fort Zachary
Taylor State Park on Key West shortly after noon. It was her
second attempt to cross the Florida Straits after failing last
year, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
About 150 people greeted Maroney as she emerged from the surf
with the help of one man.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old made the swim with the aid of a shark-proof
cage fastened to the escort boat, the "Reel Lady" Team members had
to work to repair a cage that deteriorated overnight, but Maroney
abandoned the cage about 100 meters from shore.
</P>
<P>
In June, Maroney covered 172 kilometers in 38 1/2 hours. She
gave up 19 kilometers short of her goal because of seasickness and
dehydration.  
</P>
</TEXT>
