<HEADLINE> Germany's Leica Camera Hit by Slow-Up in Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany's prestige camera producer
Leica Camera AG has been hit by a 7.4 percent drop in operating
earnings in the 1996-1997 business year, mainly due to slow
deliveries of new products in domestic markets, the company said
today.
</P>
<P>
According to Dieter Hofmann, the company's chairman of the
board, Leica's operating profits for 1996-1997 were 15.2 million
German marks, or about 9.1 million U.S. dollars. However, the
company had managed to achieved its sales target with a 10.7
percent rise in turnover to 265.6 million marks, or 159.2 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In parallel to sharp rises in turnover in Asia and the United
States, 41 percent and 47 percent respectively, Leica's sales
dropped by 6 percent in the domestic markets. 
</P>
