<HEADLINE> US Dollar Slides Below 120 yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar tumbled below 120
yen for the first time in nearly four months in New York today,
but it partly recovered and rallied against European currencies.
</P>
<P>
Supportive comments by senior Japanese officials, severe mark
weakness against the yen and the pound, and strong rallies in the
U.S. stock and bond markets combined to help the dollar recoup
somewhat from its worst extended retreat in more than 18 months,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The dollar fell as low as 117.50 yen in Asian dealings, the
lowest since January 22, before rebounding to settle in New York
at 119.30 yen, down from 120.35 yen Friday. The dollar settled at
1.7064 marks, up from 1.6869. The pound cost 1.6184 U.S. dollars,
down from 1.6205 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last month finance ministers of the G-7 suggested they would
intervene to restrain the dollar from rising further against the
yen and mark.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday:
1.4385 Swiss francs, up from 1.4235; 5.7530 French francs, up from
5.6875; 1,691.00 Italian lire, up from 1,670.75; 1.3895 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.3923. 
</P>
