<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Commander Checks Russian Missile Launch Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Army General George
Joulwan, commander of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO), today said that he is checking a report that recent
malfunctions have switched Russia's nuclear missiles to "combat
mode."
</P>
<P>
The Washington Times today reported that classified information
of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) indicated that
malfunctions have switched Russia's nuclear missiles
"spontaneously to combat mode."
</P>
<P>
Answering questions on the report, Joulwan told reporters here.
"Reports we have seen up to this date have been that the nuclear
warheads have been properly cared for."
</P>
<P>
"But this brings another bit of information and we are going to
assess that and look into it," Joulwan added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that NATO has been watching with some concern the
storage of nuclear warheads in Russia and "we have positive
feedback that it's been done correctly."
</P>
<P>
Also today, a senior Pentagon official said at the Pentagon
that he saw no new risk of accidental or unauthorized launch of
Russian nuclear missiles against the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on condition of anonymity, the official
said that there is no reason "to believe that there is a
heightened risk of unauthorized or accidental launch of Russian
nuclear missiles."
</P>
<P>
"I can tell you that I have seen nothing that indicates that
any sort of an incident occurred," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. officials made the remarks on the eve of a two-day
visit to Washington by Russian Defense Minister Igor Rodionov.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Rodionov is scheduled to meet with top U.S.
officials on bilateral military ties and security in Europe and
the western Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Rodionov will hold separate talks Tuesday with Defense
Secretary William Cohen and White House National Security Adviser
Samuel (Sandy) Berger, and meets Wednesday with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright before departing for Hawaii and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The talks will focus on increased U.S.-Russian military
cooperation, but also include NATO enlargement, European security
and the situation in the Pacific rim, the Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
Trip will be Rodionov's first to the U.S. as defense minister
and he would meet Cohen for the first time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
